"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668926","Department for Education","false","2017-01-11","<p>The Government published its response to the Early Years National Funding Formula consultation, alongside detailed tables of allocations to each local authority, on <br>1 December. Allocations are made using the Early Years National Funding Formula, which includes an Area Cost Adjustment to reflect the differing costs of childcare in different parts of the country.</p><p><br>These documents can be found at: https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/early-years-funding-changes-to-funding-for-3-and-4-year-olds</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-01-11T15:20:25.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668926/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668926/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668926/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-06","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if her Department will provide a London weighting to children eligible for the 30 hours free childcare or education offer.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","58863"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668927","Department for Education","false","2017-01-18","<p>The Universities and Colleges Admissions Service (UCAS) publishes data on applicants, applications and acceptances to full-time undergraduate courses.</p><p>There were 19,210 applicants to medicine courses in total with a 15 October 2017 UCAS deadline, 4% fewer (-890 people) than last year.</p><p>The Department engages with higher education institutions on an on-going basis, across a range of issues.</p><p><strong>The tables show the number of applicants for medicine courses with a 15 October deadline (2017 cycle) in the UK<sup>1</sup>: </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Domicile of applicant</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2017</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>UK</p></td><td><p>17,000</p></td><td><p>17,140</p></td><td><p>15,220</p></td><td><p>14,820</p></td><td><p>14,450</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>All</p></td><td><p>22,130</p></td><td><p>22,740</p></td><td><p>20,390</p></td><td><p>20,100</p></td><td><p>19,210</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Difference between cycle and 2016 cycle</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2017</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>UK</p></td><td><p>15%</p></td><td><p>16%</p></td><td><p>3%</p></td><td><p>0%</p></td><td><p>-2%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>All</p></td><td><p>10%</p></td><td><p>13%</p></td><td><p>1%</p></td><td><p>0%</p></td><td><p>-4%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The number of applications to Medicine and Dentistry courses (subject Group A) by the 15 January UCAS deadline will be published on 2 February.</p><p>Notes:</p><p>1. The figures were extracted from the UCAS October 2017 Deadline Applicant Statistics available via the following weblink:</p><p><a href="https://www.ucas.com/corporate/news-and-key-documents/news/applicant-numbers-%E2%80%98early-deadline%E2%80%99-university-courses-increase" target="_blank">https://www.ucas.com/corporate/news-and-key-documents/news/applicant-numbers-%E2%80%98early-deadline%E2%80%99-university-courses-increase</a></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","58859","2017-01-18T17:02:35.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668927/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668927/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668927/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-06","Medicine: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what discussions she has had with UK higher education institutions on the nine per cent drop in applications for medicine courses in UK universities for the 2017-18 academic year.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","58860"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668928","Department for Education","false","2017-01-13","<p>No agency or authority under the Department for Education holds data on the improper reporting of pupil exclusions.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2017-01-13T14:56:08.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668928/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668928/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668928/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-06","Pupil Exclusions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 20 December 2016 to Question 57874, whether any agency or authority under the Department for Education holds data on the improper reporting of pupil exclusions.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","58806"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668929","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-12","<p>The transit of whale meat through UK and EU ports remains a point of concern for the UK. Alongside other EU Member States, we have continued to push the European Commission to look at the scope for collective action within the EU.</p><p> </p><p>This is a complex issue involving complying with international trade rules, however, leaving the EU will present us with an opportunity to consider this issue from a different perspective.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-01-12T12:57:54.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668929/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668929/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668929/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-06","Whales: Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what discussions she has had with her EU counterparts about preventing whale meat and other whale-based products from passing through EU ports.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","58898"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668930","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-11","<p>I met the Chinese delegation to the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES) 17<sup>th</sup> Conference of Parties, including the Vice Minister of the State Forestry Administration, in London on 21 September 2016 immediately prior to the Conference. Although discussions did not specifically include the commercial breeding of tigers, we did discuss the conservation of a number of species including tigers.</p><p> </p><p>At the Conference the UK, working with Member States of the European Union and other countries, achieved strong outcomes for tigers including the agreement of proposals to scrutinise captive breeding facilities.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-01-11T15:35:24.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668930/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668930/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668930/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-06","Tigers: China","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what discussions she has had with her Chinese counterpart on preventing the breeding of tigers for commercial purposes.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","58899"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668931","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-11","<p>The Secretary of State has not held discussions with the Environment Agency regarding the enforcement of the waste hierarchy.</p><p> </p><p>The Environment Agency always promotes observance of the waste hierarchy and takes a risk based, proportionate approach to enforcement. It rewards good performance and targets regulatory effort at higher-risk operators with the worst environmental performance.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-01-11T12:37:22.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668931/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668931/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668931/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-06","Waste Management","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what discussions she has had with the Environment Agency about (a) its responsibility to enforce the waste hierarchy and (b) cases in which that hierarchy has not been observed.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","58723"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668932","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-12","<p>Local planning authorities have a wide range of powers to tackle breaches of planning control. Failure to comply with a planning condition would normally be dealt with by serving a breach of condition notice or an enforcement notice requiring the recipient to remedy the breach. Full details of their powers can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/ensuring-effective-enforcement" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/guidance/ensuring-effective-enforcement</a>.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2017-01-12T16:42:18.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668932/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668932/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668932/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-01-06","Floods: Property Development","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what powers local authorities have to enforce flood planning conditions on new houses being built.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","59005"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668933","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-11","<p>Consultations on planning for housing in areas at risk of flooding are primarily the responsibility of the local planning authorities. The Department has no role in these consultations. However, in relation to planning applications in Flood Zones 2 and 3, the Environment Agency is a statutory consultee and so must be consulted by the planning authority. There are also statutory requirements for local planning authorities to consult the Environment Agency on the preparation of local plans.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-01-11T12:54:45.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668933/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668933/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668933/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-06","Floods: Property Development","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what role her Department has on planning consultations for housing in areas at risk of flooding.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","59006"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668934","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-11","<p>The government has invested £29.8 million for flood and coastal risk management schemes in 2015/16 and plans to invest a further £91.3 million by March 2021 to reduce the risks of flooding or coastal erosion across Lancashire.</p><p> </p><p>This includes investments to the recently completed Anchorsholme Coastal Defence Protection Scheme, where the government has invested £28.7 million to better protect 4,415 properties, and for the Rossall Coastal Defence Protection Scheme, due for completion in September 2017 where the government will invest around £47.5 million to better protect 7,497 properties.</p><p> </p><p>A further £9.7 million of government funding has been allocated to the Morecambe Wave Reflection Wall, expected for completion in 2019 and better protecting 8,127 properties. The government is also planning to invest £17.4 million on the Fairhaven and Church Scar Coast Protection Scheme, which is expected to start construction in spring 2017 and will better protect 1,357 properties.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-01-11T12:57:19.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668934/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668934/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668934/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-06","Flood Control: Lancashire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps her Department is taking to prevent flooding in Lancashire.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","59007"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668935","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-16","<p>The rapid changes taking place in the Arctic pose immense challenges for Arctic States as well as for neighbouring countries including the UK. The Government is actively engaged in protecting the Arctic environment and ecological system. The UK promotes greater understanding of the Arctic through international scientific collaboration and the development of policy based on sound science. The Natural Environment Research Council (NERC) works with other countries to build an understanding of the threats and opportunities posed by climate change. The Joint Nature Conservation Committee (JNCC) works with the Arctic Council to protect migratory bird species across the Arctic and the UK. The UK's leading role in reducing human-generated greenhouse gas emissions is vital to safeguarding the Arctic environment, as is our engagement in key international organisations. A £16 million research programme funded by NERC over the next 5 years will focus on the effects of changes to sea ice cover on the marine eco-system in the Arctic.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-01-16T17:36:38.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668935/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668935/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668935/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-06","Arctic: Environment Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he is taking to protect the Arctic environment and its eco-system.","false","Biography information for Mr Ranil Jayawardena","North East Hampshire","Mr Ranil Jayawardena","58978"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668936","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-12","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the reply given to the hon. Member for Northampton South, David Mackintosh, on 11 January 2016, PQ UIN 58249.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-01-12T13:04:32.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668936/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668936/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668936/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-06","Wildlife: Smuggling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, with reference to her Department's press release, UK leading global fight against illegal wildlife trade, published on 17 November 2016, how and in what areas the additional funding to tackle the illegal wildlife trade will be spent.","false","Biography information for Mr Ranil Jayawardena","North East Hampshire","Mr Ranil Jayawardena","58979"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668937","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-16","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union (DExEU) under Rt Hon David Davis is the lead department supporting the Prime Minister in her negotiations for leaving the EU. The Foreign and Commonwealth Office also has a key role to play, and staff in the FCO's Europe Directorate lead on providing advice to FCO Ministers on EU-related issues. Staff in other Directorates in London, as well as in our diplomatic missions around the world, can also work on EU-related issues. Their work will support negotiations after Article 50 has been invoked.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-01-16T17:34:35.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668937/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668937/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668937/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-06","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many of his Department's staff he plans to work on conducting negotiations with the EU after Article 50 has been triggered.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","58993"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668938","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-16","<p>The UK’s objectives are to strengthen our partnership with Turkey to help keep the UK safer and more prosperous - including working together for regional stability and security, ensuring the safety of British tourists, and improving markets for British exporters and growing inward investment.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-01-16T17:33:18.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668938/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668938/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668938/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-06","Turkey: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what the objectives of the Government's diplomatic and political policy on Turkey are for 2017; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","58983"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668939","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-16","<p>The UK and Pakistan are joined by enduring bonds of friendship and partnership. We have a strong bilateral relationship and are keen to make it even stronger.</p><p>On 14 August 2017 Pakistan will celebrate the 70<sup>th</sup> Anniversary of the creation of Pakistan. With an estimated 1.2 million people of Pakistani heritage in the UK, this is an opportunity to highlight our common history, cultural and people to people links, as well as to deepen our partnership for the future.</p><p>Pakistan is making improvements in security, economically and politically and is delivering better lives for its people. The UK's political priorities in Pakistan for 2017 include the continued strengthening of democracy ahead of elections in 2018; the consolidation of economic and security gains made over recent years through relevant reforms; and an improvement in regional relations that leads to a more stable South Asia, enabling greater economic growth and prosperity. We are making efforts to enhance trade and investment between our countries. And, alongside this, we remain committed to supporting Pakistan in building a society where the rights of all its citizens are respected and their prospects in health, education and employment are improved, all of which is an investment in the UK's security and national interest. Finally, the UK and Pakistan will continue to tackle jointly threats such as illegal migration, organised crime and terrorism, whilst working together to enhance Pakistan's criminal justice system.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-01-16T15:15:21.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668939/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668939/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668939/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-06","Pakistan: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what the objectives of the Government's diplomatic and political policy on Pakistan are for 2017; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","58982"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668940","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-11","<p>In December, the Ambassador met with Mrs Zaghari-Ratcliffe's family in Tehran. He has also spoken by telephone to Mrs Zaghari-Ratcliffe's husband in the UK to explain what the Embassy is doing to assist her. The Ambassador most recently met and raised Mrs Zaghari-Ratcliffe's case with the Iranian Deputy Foreign Minister on 4 January. He will continue to raise her case with the Iranian Government at every available opportunity.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-11T16:38:37.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668940/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668940/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668940/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-06","Nazanin Zaghari-Ratcliffe","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent steps HM Ambassador to Iran has taken to support (a) Nazanin Zaghari-Ratcliffe and (b) Nazanin Zaghari-Ratcliffe's family.","false","Biography information for Gavin Robinson","Belfast East","Gavin Robinson","58960"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668941","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-16","<p>The Government's objectives in respect of Russia are to protect UK interests and those of our allies and partners; to uphold the rules-based international order in the face of Russian challenges; to engage with Russia in key areas of shared interest; to promote our values, including the rule of law and human rights; and to build stronger links between the British and Russian people more widely. We continue to have significant differences with Russia, notably over their actions in Syria and ongoing destabilisation of Ukraine. It would be a mistake to go back to business as usual whilst these are unresolved, so a twin track strategy of vigilance and of engagement is what is required.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-01-16T17:45:36.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668941/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668941/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668941/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-06","Russia: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what the objectives of the Government's diplomatic and political policy on Russia are for 2017; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","58984"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668942","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-16","<p>The UK’s longstanding position is clear: we support a negotiated settlement leading to a safe and secure Israel living alongside a viable and sovereign Palestinian state based on 1967 borders with agreed land swaps, Jerusalem as the shared capital of both states, and a just, fair and agreed settlement for refugees. We are encouraging both sides to resume direct bilateral negotiations and we work through international organisations, including the UN and EU, to encourage Israel and the Palestinian Authority to take steps that rebuild trust.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-16T16:51:27.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668942/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668942/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668942/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-06","Palestinians: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what the objectives of the Government's diplomatic and political policy on Palestine are for 2017; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","58985"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668943","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-16","<p>The United Kingdom is committed to conserving Asian elephants and recognises the growing threats to their populations. We have been working internationally through the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES) to increase protection for Asian elephants, specifically with regard to the illegal cross border trade in live elephants which has been used to supply the tourism and logging industries. In August, officials from DEFRA met Indian officials in London to discuss the treatment of captive Asian elephants, the illegal trade in live elephants and the broader illegal wildlife trade. Whilst HMG does not offer advice to British citizens on ethical issues, such as the practice of keeping animals in captivity abroad, we will continue to work with the relevant government authorities and non-government organisations on this important issue.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-01-16T15:17:01.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668943/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668943/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668943/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-06","Tourism: Elephants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will take steps to ensure that UK citizens travelling to India, Thailand and other elephant-range states are made aware of the illegal practice of capturing and breaking young elephants for use in the tourism industry.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","58743"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668944","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-16","<p>We are aware of reports about the incident which took place in Bangalore on New Year's Eve, and welcome the action taken by the police who have arrested four people in relation to this.</p><p>The UK is committed to tackling violence against women and girls around the world. We work with the Indian government and civil society organisations to support their efforts to tackle this critical challenge including through a variety of project work covering key issues such as promoting women and girls' rights.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-01-16T17:41:02.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668944/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668944/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668944/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-06","India: Sexual Offences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of women's rights in Bangalore after reports of alleged sexual assaults on women in that country on New Year's Eve 2016.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","58756"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668945","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-16","<p>I condemn the attack on the Ahmadiyya mosque in Chakwal on 12 December. The Government strongly condemns the persecution of all minorities, including the targeting of people based on their beliefs.</p><p>We regularly raise our concerns about the protection of minority communities, including religious minorities, with the Government of Pakistan. During my visit to Pakistan last week, I discussed the protection of religious minorities, including the Ahmadiyya, with Kamran Michael, Pakistani Minister for Human Rights, and Barrister Zafarullah Khan, the Prime Minister's Special Assistant for Human Rights. The Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Mr Boris Johnson), raised religious tolerance and the importance of safeguarding the rights of all Pakistan's citizens when he visited Pakistan in November 2016. The Government continues to urge Pakistan to honour in practice its human rights obligations, including those related to religious minorities, and to uphold the rule of law.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-01-16T15:13:11.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668945/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668945/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668945/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-06","Pakistan: Ahmadiyya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether the Government has asked the Pakistani High Commissioner to lift the seal on the Ahmadi mosque in Chakwal.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","58775"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668946","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-16","<p>Sir Tim Barrow was appointed as the new Permanent Representative to the European Union on Wednesday 4 January, and has already taken up his role.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-01-16T17:37:22.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668946/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668946/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668946/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-06","UK Permanent Representation to the EU: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what the earliest date is on which the Government expects (a) to appoint a replacement for Sir Ivan Rogers and (b) for his successor to be in post.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","58776"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668947","Department of Health","false","2017-01-16","<p>The Government supports the establishment of lawful and ethical organ donation and transplantation programmes to address the world-wide shortage of organs for transplant and a range of action to discourage organ trafficking, transplant tourism and commercialism. The United Kingdom formally signed the Council of Europe Convention Against Trafficking in Human Organs on 25 March 2015 and has laws and protocols in place to ensure well-regulated practice to prevent organ trafficking in the UK.</p><p> </p><p>The Government supports the Declaration of Istanbul, which encourages all countries to draw up legal and professional frameworks to govern organ donation and transplantation activities. We have also participated in the development of the World Health Organization Guiding Principles to ensure that human material removed from deceased and living donors for the purpose of transplantation only takes place according to agreed ethical principles.</p><p> </p><p>Patients receiving transplants outside the UK will be subject to the relevant regulatory regime in place and should be aware of the risks, including possible prosecution for non-compliance with relevant local and international provisions, poor donor care, poorer graft survival, infection and in extreme cases, death.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-01-16T16:57:10.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668947/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668947/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668947/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-06","Organs: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps the Government is taking to prevent British citizens from receiving organs overseas from the forced organ harvesting trade.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","58668"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668948","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-16","<p>We do not hold accurate numbers of Yemeni civilians who have been killed in airstrikes. We deeply regret the loss of civilian lives in any conflict and continue to urge the Yemeni parties to implement a sustainable cessation of hostilities and work towards reaching a peace agreement for the sake of the people of Yemen.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-16T16:47:42.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668948/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668948/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668948/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-06","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment his Department has made of the number of Yemeni civilians who have been killed in airstrikes since the bombing of a funeral hall in Sanaa on 10 October 2016.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","58672"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668949","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-16","<p>I refer the Hon. Member to my answer of 24 October 2016 (PQ 48760).</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-16T16:49:03.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668949/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668949/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668949/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-06","Palestinians: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to work with the Palestinian Authority to promote gender equality in the Palestinian territories.","false","Biography information for Mr Ivan Lewis","Bury South","Mr Ivan Lewis","58704"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668950","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-16","<p>​The resolution was an Egyptian draft and not UK co-sponsored. The UK engaged with security council members before the UN Security Council Resolution 2334 (2016) vote, as we do with all Security Council products. Where we did engage we worked to secure a balanced text that includes calls to end incitement and terrorism .</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-16T14:07:48.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668950/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668950/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668950/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-06","Israeli Settlements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what formal and informal discussions his Department had with the US administration before the UN Security Council Resolution 2334 (2016) vote was taken.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","58875"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668951","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-16","<p>​The resolution was an Egyptian draft and not UK co-sponsored. The UK engaged with the text, as we do all Security Council products. Where we did engage, we worked to secure a balanced text that includes calls to end incitement and terrorism We would not have voted for any text without those balancing elements.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-16T14:09:31.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668951/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668951/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668951/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-06","Israeli Settlements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what support his Department provided in the drafting process for UN Security Council Resolution 2334 (2016).","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","58876"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668952","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-16","<p>​The relevant UK ministers were aware of the text of the resolution before the vote took place. The UK voted for UN Security Council Resolution 2334 because of our support for the two state solution and commitment to Israel as the Jewish homeland.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-16T14:12:06.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668952/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668952/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668952/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-06","Israeli Settlements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether Ministers of his Department were made aware of the final text of UN Security Council Resolution 2334 (2016) before the vote on that resolution took place.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","58877"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668953","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-16","<p>The resolution was an Egyptian draft and not UK co-sponsored. The UK engaged with the text, as we do all Security Council products. Where we did engage we worked to secure a balanced text that includes calls to end incitement and terrorism We would not have voted for any text without those balancing elements.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-16T14:13:59.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668953/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668953/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668953/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-06","Israeli Settlements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what contribution his Department made to the drafting and promoting of UN Security Council Resolution 2334.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","58927"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668954","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-16","<p>​The Foreign and Commonwealth Office discussed the UK’s voting position on UNSCR 2334 with 10 Downing Street prior to the vote in the UN Security Council. The UK’s support for UNSCR 2334 is consistent with our long held position that Israeli settlement activity is illegal and undermines the viability of two states for two peoples. As the Prime Minister, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Maidenhead (Mrs May) stated in her speech to the Conservative Friends of Israel in December, the UK remains one of Israel’s strongest friends, but it is important as a true friend to stress that settlements are illegal.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-16T14:05:20.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668954/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668954/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668954/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-06","Israeli Settlements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions his Department held with 10 Downing Street before the UN Security Council Resolution 2334 vote took place in December 2016.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","58870"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668955","Department of Health","false","2017-01-11","<p>The Department expects to publish the new national strategy for carers in the spring. No publication date has yet been set.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-01-11T14:22:42.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668955/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668955/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668955/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-06","Carers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, in which month the Carers Strategy for England will be published.","false","Biography information for Mr Mark Prisk","Hertford and Stortford","Mr Mark Prisk","58843"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668956","Department of Health","false","2017-01-16","<p>The Department has made no formal assessment of the recommendations in Action Cerebral Palsy's audit of cerebral palsy provision, ‘Variations in Care’.</p><p> </p><p>Information of the number of children born with cerebral palsy in each year is not held centrally.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","58866","2017-01-16T16:29:57.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668956/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668956/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668956/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-06","Cerebral Palsy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what records his Department holds of the number of children born with cerebral palsy each year in (a) each Community Care Group area, (b) each local authority area, (c) each region and (d) nationally.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","58867"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668957","Department of Health","false","2017-01-16","<p>As part of the Serious Illness Care Programme pilot, patient conversations are due to be completed in summer 2017. The Research and Innovation Directorate at Clatterbridge Cancer Centre NHS Foundation Trust will then evaluate the outcome data collected, so that they can complete the pilot report.</p><p> </p><p>A variety of qualitative and quantitative measures will be collected and assessed as part of the pilots. This includes assessments of patients’ understanding and control of their health care, and their quality of life.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","58816","2017-01-16T16:38:00.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668957/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668957/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668957/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-06","Palliative Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 20 December 2016 to Question 57868, when he plans to publish the outcomes of testing the new innovative approach to serious illness conversations at the New Care Model sites at Airedale and Southend.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","58810"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668958","Department of Health","false","2017-01-16","<p>The information requested is in the attached document.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-01-16T17:09:11.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668958/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668958/answer","PQ58856 GP-Patient Ratio 11th Jan.xlsx","GP to patient ratio","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668958/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-06","Doctors' List of Patients","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the GP-to-patient ratio is in (a) North Lancashire Community Care Group (CCG), (b) Blackpool, Fylde and Wyre CCG and (c) England.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","58856"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668959","Department of Health","false","2017-01-16","<p>The Department has made no formal assessment of the recommendations in Action Cerebral Palsy's audit of cerebral palsy provision, ‘Variations in Care’.</p><p> </p><p>Information of the number of children born with cerebral palsy in each year is not held centrally.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","58867","2017-01-16T16:29:57.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668959/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668959/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668959/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-06","Cerebral Palsy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether his Department has made an assessment of the recommendations in Action Cerebral Palsy's audit of cerebral palsy provision, Variations in Care; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","58866"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668960","Department of Health","false","2017-01-16","<p>Public Health England is currently developing a generic approach which will enable us to cover a range of symptoms in one campaign. A regional pilot campaign to raise awareness of a range of abdominal symptoms that can indicate a wider number of cancers including ovarian (and the need to visit the doctor promptly with these symptoms) will run from 9 February until 31 March 2017 in the East and West Midlands. This work has been developed with the help of a number of experts, including clinicians and charities.</p><p> </p><p>The regional pilot will be evaluated and results will help inform decisions about how to expand this campaign in future.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-01-16T16:34:51.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668960/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668960/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668960/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-06","Ovarian Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to raise awareness of the symptoms of ovarian cancer.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","58857"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668961","Department of Health","false","2017-01-11","<p>Our ambition is for everyone approaching the end of life to receive high quality care that reflects their individual needs, choices and preferences. On 5 July 2016, we set out our commitment to end of life care in the Government response to the independent Review of Choice in End of Life Care. In 2016, the National End of Life Care Programme Board, chaired by Sir Bruce Keogh, NHS England Medical Director, was set up to oversee the implementation of the commitment.</p><p> </p><p>The commitments in the response will address the unacceptable variation in access to end of life care and the quality of care. They will put in place improvements in all settings where end of life care is delivered, including in hospital, in a care home, or at home, and improve access to specialist palliative care advice through urgent and emergency care clinical hubs.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-01-11T15:30:16.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668961/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668961/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668961/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-06","Palliative Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that palliative care is accessible to all people who need it.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","58799"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668962","Department of Health","false","2017-01-16","<p>The National Institute for Health Research (NIHR) and an Independent Trial Steering Committee, appointed by the NIHR, assessed the study protocols during the course of the research. No concerns were raised. The study was also subject to scrutiny by the sponsor and ethical committees, as is the usual course of activity in such a trial.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-01-16T16:53:34.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668962/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668962/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668962/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-06","Clinical Trials: Nottingham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will make an assessment of whether the proper protocols were followed in the CLOTHES trial at Nottingham Clinical Trials Unit.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","58811"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668963","Department of Health","false","2017-01-16","<p>The National Institute for Health Research (NIHR) appointed an Independent Trial Steering Committee to oversee this independent trial. The study team also reported regularly to the NIHR, as a condition of their funding contract and in accordance with their membership of the NIHR portfolio.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-01-16T16:54:26.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668963/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668963/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668963/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-06","Clinical Trials: Nottingham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will take steps to investigate why no independent audit body observed the CLOTHES trial at Nottingham Clinical Trials Unit in any assessment of that trial.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","58812"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668964","Department of Health","false","2017-01-11","<p>This information is not available in the format requested.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-01-11T14:58:49.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668964/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668964/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668964/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-06","Accident and Emergency Departments: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, (a) how many people had to wait in corridors and other locations prior to being admitted to and (b) what the average waiting time was to be seen at accident and emergency units at (i) Royal Preston Hospital, (ii) Royal Blackburn Hospital, (iii) Royal Lancaster Infirmary and (iv) Blackpool Victoria Hospital on each day from 23 December 2016 to 2 January 2017.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","58828"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668965","Department of Health","false","2017-01-16","<p>Health Education England’s (HEE) End of Life Care Core Skills Education and Training Framework is in the final stages of comment and amendment by the steering group following a consultation period. HEE are hoping to publish the framework in early 2017.</p><p> </p><p>The Royal College of Midwives (RCM), the Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists, the Stillbirth &amp; Neonatal Death Charity (SANDS) and other charities have agreed to design a new bereavement care pathway, rather than a new competency framework specifically for midwives, to improve the bereavement care provided by all professions.</p><p> </p><p>Additionally, the Nursing Medical Council is undertaking a review of midwifery standards and competencies, due to be completed in 2018. SANDS are also running bereavement training days, accredited by the RCM, for both student midwives and fully trained midwives.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","58817","2017-01-16T16:13:45.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668965/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668965/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668965/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-06","Palliative Care: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 20 December 2016 to Question 57868, when Health Education England plans to publish its core competency framework for the standardisation of end of life care training.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","58815"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668966","Department of Health","false","2017-01-16","<p>The National Institute for Health Research (NIHR) Healthcare Technology Assessment (HTA) Programme follows a process of expert review through which research briefs, research applications and final reports are critically assessed by relevant individuals unconnected to both the decision making body and those who have prepared the material being assessed. The practice of peer review is very commonly used to inform decision making for scientific publications and grant funding. It involves colleagues in a relevant field of expertise, including patients, members of the public, subject experts, clinical staff, service managers and public health professionals. The NIHR selects all reviewers.</p><p> </p><p>Expert review was undertaken for the CLOTHES trial, in accordance with NIHR HTA policy. This included one public and four expert representatives. Checks were carried out to ensure that all reviewers were suitably qualified and were not conflicted.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-01-16T16:52:48.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668966/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668966/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668966/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-06","Clinical Trials: Nottingham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will make an assessment of the robustness of the peer review system for clinical trials especially in relation to reviewing the CLOTHES trial at Nottingham Clinical Trials Unit.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","58813"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668967","Department of Health","false","2017-01-11","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-01-11T14:59:57.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668967/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668967/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668967/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-06","Ambulance Services: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many ambulance crews were provided by (a) St John's Ambulance, (b) Jigsaw Medical Services and (c) other providers to North West Ambulance Services on each day from 23 December 2016 to 2 January 2017.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","58829"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668968","Department of Health","false","2017-01-16","<p>As part of the Serious Illness Care Programme pilot, patient conversations are due to be completed in summer 2017. The Research and Innovation Directorate at Clatterbridge Cancer Centre NHS Foundation Trust will then evaluate the outcome data collected, so that they can complete the pilot report.</p><p> </p><p>A variety of qualitative and quantitative measures will be collected and assessed as part of the pilots. This includes assessments of patients’ understanding and control of their health care, and their quality of life.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","58810","2017-01-16T16:38:00.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668968/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668968/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668968/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-06","Palliative Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 20 December 2016 to Question 57868, what outcomes are being measured at the New Care Model sites at Airedale and Southend with regard to the new innovative approach to serious illness conversations.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","58816"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668969","Department of Health","false","2017-01-16","<p>The National Institute for Health Research (NIHR) Healthcare Technology Assessment (HTA) Programme has a clear conflict of interests procedure to ensure that each application is judged on merit.</p><p> </p><p>Any panel member on the NIHR HTA Commissioning Board with a conflict of interest is asked to leave the room during any discussion or decision on these projects or issues.</p><p> </p><p>Any conflicts are recorded in the minutes and made public after the meeting.</p><p> </p><p>The NIHR HTA Commissioning Board agreed to fund the CLOTHES trial at the Board’s July 2012 meeting and the public minutes can be found here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.nets.nihr.ac.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0016/13525/minutes-jul-2012.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.nets.nihr.ac.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0016/13525/minutes-jul-2012.pdf</a></p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-01-16T16:51:52.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668969/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668969/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668969/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-06","Clinical Trials: Nottingham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will investigate the potential conflict of interest at the Health Technology Assessment Programme for those people responsible for awarding funding for the CLOTHES clinical trials who were also heading the Nottingham Clinical Trials Unit to which funding was ultimately granted.","false","Biography information for Grant Shapps","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","58814"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668970","Department of Health","false","2017-01-11","<p>The Test Bed Programme is a joint initiative between the Department (including the Office for Life Sciences) and NHS England. It is creating industry-National Health Service partnerships to test combinations of innovations in technologies (including Internet of Things technologies) with innovations in how NHS services are delivered to improve health and care outcomes at the same or lower cost than existing practice.</p><p> </p><p>There are seven test bed sites across England responding to locally identified clinical challenges. For example, patients with diabetes, in the West of England test bed site, are being equipped with remote monitoring and coaching technology to allow them to better self-manage their condition. All the test beds are now implementing their plans, with a focus on patient recruitment, deploying technological solutions, testing combinations and starting data collection for their evaluation phase. They are due to complete in March 2018 and information on the effectiveness of their combinatorial innovations will be published soon after.</p><p> </p><p>Further details of the seven Test Bed sites can be found here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/ourwork/innovation/test-beds/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/ourwork/innovation/test-beds/</a></p><p> </p><p>NHS England and the Department have put in place a package of support for the test beds including solving day-to-day operational issues as well as a programme of work exploring the system tools and levers that will be needed to support the wider adoption of successful innovations. For example, successful innovations may be funded the new innovation tariff developed by NHS England or through other national programmes.</p><p> </p><p>Evaluation is central to the Test Bed programme. We want to understand the impact of the new combinations of innovations within each test bed, as well as the overall success of the programme. To this end, the test beds will undertake local evaluations of impact and value of the innovations for patients, the local health system and innovators. These local evaluations will be complemented by a national evaluation that will develop a framework that can be used to evaluate future innovations of this nature. It will build on the local evaluations by developing an approach which distils the outcomes and efficiency measurements from each Test Bed into a national framework.</p><p> </p><p>The evaluations will be made available on completion of the programme.</p><p> </p><p>Total test bed funding across the seven sites to date is approximately £4 million. Over the lifetime of the programme (two years), innovator partners would have contributed an estimated £18 million to the NHS.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","58831 ; 58832 ; 58833","2017-01-11T17:55:31.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668970/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668970/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668970/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-06","NHS: Innovation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps NHS England is taking to measure the effect of NHS test beds on patient outcomes, efficiency and value for money; and what data is available on the effect of each innovation to date.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","58830"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668971","Department of Health","false","2017-01-16","<p>Health Education England’s (HEE) End of Life Care Core Skills Education and Training Framework is in the final stages of comment and amendment by the steering group following a consultation period. HEE are hoping to publish the framework in early 2017.</p><p> </p><p>The Royal College of Midwives (RCM), the Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists, the Stillbirth &amp; Neonatal Death Charity (SANDS) and other charities have agreed to design a new bereavement care pathway, rather than a new competency framework specifically for midwives, to improve the bereavement care provided by all professions.</p><p> </p><p>Additionally, the Nursing Medical Council is undertaking a review of midwifery standards and competencies, due to be completed in 2018. SANDS are also running bereavement training days, accredited by the RCM, for both student midwives and fully trained midwives.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","58815","2017-01-16T16:13:45.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668971/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668971/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/668971/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-06","Midwives: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 20 December 2016 to Question 57868, when Health Education England plans to publish the new competency framework for all midwifery staff on basic bereavement training that is being developed with NHS England and the Royal College of Midwives.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","58817"
