"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669116","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-12","<p>‘Improving Lives: The Work Health and Disability Green Paper’ was published in October 2016 and was a joint publication by the Department for Work and Pensions and Department of Health. The Departments worked closely with Public Health England during the development of the Green Paper. Ministers and officials therefore meet on an on-going basis and officials work together in the joint DWP/DH Work and Health Unit. The Green Paper makes a specific commitment to build the evidence base on long-term health conditions. Both Departments will jointly consider next steps, which will be determined by the responses received through the national consultation, which is underway currently.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-01-12T16:30:57.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669116/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669116/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669116/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-06","Employment: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what meetings (a) Ministers and (b) officials of his Department have had with (i) the Department of Health and (ii) Public Health England on developing the evidence base on long-term health conditions, including degenerative and fluctuating health conditions and work outcomes following the publication in November 2016 of the work, health and disability green paper: improving lives.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","58886"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669117","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-11","<p>It is not known precisely how many Jobcentres are subject to planning applications across our entire estate at this time. This is because any party can make a planning application for a change of use for a building without the involvement of either the landlord or current tenants.</p><p> </p><p>DWP will identify this information as part of conveyancing activity on buildings it is planning to retain or acquire.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-11T17:40:26.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669117/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669117/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669117/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-06","Jobcentres: Change of Use","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many jobcentre offices in the UK are subject to live planning applications that would change the use of those premises.","false","Biography information for Carol Monaghan","Glasgow North West","Carol Monaghan","58905"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669118","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-11","<p>The Department spent the following amounts on providers of the Work Programme.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£million</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>635.9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>573.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>416.4</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-11T17:39:29.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669118/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669118/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669118/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-06","Work Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how much his Department has spent on companies that provide Work Programme services in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Carol Monaghan","Glasgow North West","Carol Monaghan","58906"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669119","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-11","<p>Although financial support under the New Enterprise Allowance (NEA) scheme is not available to Work Programme participants, Work Programme providers are free to support participants to set up a business.</p><p> </p><p>A core principle of the Work Programme is that providers are free to offer the interventions they feel are right for the individual, at the right time. This includes providing support and advice on self employment where it is the right option for the individual.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-11T15:01:25.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669119/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669119/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669119/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-06","Work Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what small business start-up grants are available to people on the Work Programme.","false","Biography information for Carol Monaghan","Glasgow North West","Carol Monaghan","58907"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669120","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-11","<p>The Department uses prices and earnings indices published in October of the previous year to ensure that it has sufficient time to complete the legislative and operational changes required before new rates can be introduced at the start of the new financial year.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-01-11T15:36:29.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669120/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669120/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669120/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-06","State Retirement Pensions: Uprating","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, for what reason annual increases to state pensions are made with reference to the inflation figures from October of the previous year.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","58909"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669121","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-16","<p>The Prime Minister has made clear that she wants to protect the rights of British citizens currently living in European member states, in the same way that we want to protect the status of EU nationals already living here. The reciprocal rights and entitlements that will apply following the UK’s exit are subject to the wider negotiation on our future relationship with the EU. At every step of this negotiation the Government will seek to ensure the best possible outcome for the British people, at home and overseas.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-16T14:37:17.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669121/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669121/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669121/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-06","National Insurance Contributions: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that working and benefits provision is in place in the event that expats living abroad must return to the UK after the UK leaves the EU (a) in general and (b) for those expats who may not have made national insurance contributions in recent years.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","58774"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669122","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-10","<p>In his Written Ministerial Statement to the House of Commons on 15<sup>th</sup> September 2016 the Secretary of State confirmed that the new funding model will ensure that the supported housing sector will be funded at the same level it would have otherwise been in 2019/20, taking into account the effect of Government policy on social sector rents.</p><p>An online consultation on this new model seeking the views of the sector was launched on 21<sup>st</sup> November 2016 and will run until 13<sup>th</sup> February 2017 and can be accessed from the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/funding-for-supported-housing" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/funding-for-supported-housing</a></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-01-10T15:20:27.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669122/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669122/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669122/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-06","Supported Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps he is taking to ensure that funding is provided to older people and other vulnerable people so that those people can access adequate supported housing.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","58752"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669123","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-10","<p>In his Written Ministerial Statement to the House of Commons on 15<sup>th</sup> September 2016 the Secretary of State confirmed that the Government was committed to protecting and boosting the supply of supported housing and ensuring it provides value for money and works for those who use it as well as those who pay for it.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-01-10T15:24:25.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669123/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669123/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669123/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-06","Housing Benefit: Supported Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the effect of the housing benefit cap on the affordability of housing for claimants living in supported housing.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","58753"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669124","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-11","<p>I refer the Honourable Gentleman to the written answer I provided to the member for Glasgow East on 21 November 2016 to PQ53995.</p><p> </p><p>Further to this, I announced the scope of the 2017 Review of automatic enrolment in a Ministerial Statement to the House on 12 December 2016. Among other matters, this review will consider how the growing group of self-employed people can be helped to save for their retirement.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-01-11T17:04:29.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669124/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669124/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669124/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-06","Self-employed: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps the Government is taking to improve access to pensions for self-employed people.","false","Biography information for Sir David Crausby","Bolton North East","Sir David Crausby","58733"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669125","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-16","<p>So far over 7 million people have been automatically enrolled into a workplace pension and more than 370,000 employers have declared their compliance.</p><p> </p><p>We anticipate that around 10 million people will be saving or saving more as a result of automatic enrolment by 2018, generating an estimated £17 billion extra pension savings per year by 2019/20.</p><p> </p><p>9 out of 10 workers are choosing to remain in their workplace pension scheme after being automatically enrolled.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-01-16T14:29:12.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669125/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669125/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669125/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-06","Occupational Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the uptake of workplace pensions since that scheme's inception.","false","Biography information for Sir David Crausby","Bolton North East","Sir David Crausby","58734"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669126","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-16","<p>Figures for overpayments in Working Tax Credits and Child Tax Credits claims in 2014-15 can be found on page 8 of the Child and Working Tax Credits, Finalised Annual Awards, Supplement on Payments National Statistics, which is available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/525468/cwtc_awards_sup.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/525468/cwtc_awards_sup.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>Due to the nature of Tax Credits payments it is not possible to divide overpayments between Working Tax Credits and Child Tax Credits. The equivalent information for 2015-16 will be published in May 2017.</p><p> </p><p>Recovering overpayments from those Tax Credit customers who continue to be in award is an automated process. HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) has teams to deal with cases where an overpayment is disputed or where a customer informs HMRC they are in hardship. Figures for the administrative costs for the specific aspects of this work that relate to recovering overpayments are not available.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-01-16T16:27:11.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669126/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669126/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669126/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-06","Working Tax Credit: Overpayments","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much his Department overpaid in working tax credit claims in the last financial year; and what the estimated cost is of recovering those overpayments.","false","Biography information for Sir David Crausby","Bolton North East","Sir David Crausby","58735"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669127","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-16","<p>HM Revenue and Customs published Child Benefit, Child Tax Credit and Working Tax Credit Take-up Rates 2014-15 on 14th December 2016, and is available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/child-benefit-child-tax-credit-ctc-and-working-tax-credit-wtc-take-up-rates-2014-to-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/child-benefit-child-tax-credit-ctc-and-working-tax-credit-wtc-take-up-rates-2014-to-2015</a></p><p> </p><p>Table 1a (page 14) provides information on the amount of tax credits unclaimed by those eligible for Working Tax Credit. Information for 2015-16 is not currently available.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-01-16T16:25:36.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669127/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669127/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669127/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-06","Working Tax Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the estimated amount of unclaimed entitlement to working tax credits was in the last financial year.","false","Biography information for Sir David Crausby","Bolton North East","Sir David Crausby","58736"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669128","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-16","<p>We do not make an assessment of the overall effect of ‘false self-employment’ on welfare benefit entitlements.</p><p> </p><p>RSA Chief Executive Matthew Taylor is currently leading an independent review which will consider employment practices in the modern economy.</p><p> </p><p>Universal Credit simplifies the benefits system by bringing together a range of working age benefits, providing support for both claimants who are not working and those who are working, whether employed or self-employed. UC claimants are required to provide evidence of their self-employment as a condition of receiving benefits.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-16T15:57:23.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669128/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669128/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669128/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-06","Self-employed: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the effect of false self-employment on benefit entitlements.","false","Biography information for Sir David Crausby","Bolton North East","Sir David Crausby","58737"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669129","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-16","<p>The information requested on Universal Credit is not available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>However, there was an average of 1,700 self-employed households in receipt of tax credits in Bolton North East during 2014-15.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-16T15:52:48.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669129/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669129/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669129/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-06","Self-employed: Bolton North East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people who are certified as self-employed in Bolton North East constituency are in receipt of in-work benefits.","false","Biography information for Sir David Crausby","Bolton North East","Sir David Crausby","58732"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669130","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-11","<p>This information requested is not available and would incur disproportionate cost to provide.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","58713 ; 58715","2017-01-11T15:07:35.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669130/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669130/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669130/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-06","Income Support: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many claimants attending Bridgeton Jobcentre Plus are in receipt of income support.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","58693"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669131","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-11","<p>We will be undertaking an equality analysis as part of the detailed planning for service reconfiguration. This will include feedback from public consultation in those locations where this applies.</p><p> </p><p>The equality analysis and public consultation will help establish any impacts that additional travel will have on customers and inform decisions about additional provision, such as Outreach services. Current guidance makes alternative provision for those with mobility problems if they have a mental or physical disability, which restricts their mobility.</p><p>.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-11T16:48:27.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669131/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669131/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669131/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-06","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the effect that additional travelling will have on individuals with mobility problems in the event that the Jobcentre Plus office closures in Glasgow go ahead.","false","Biography information for Natalie McGarry","Glasgow East","Natalie McGarry","58711"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669132","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-11","<p>The department is committed to retaining an accessible Jobcentre network and continuing to serve customers in all areas of the country. Travel time by public transport is one of a number of factors that have informed our proposals for our future Jobcentre network. Where we propose to close a Jobcentre, customers will be advised on alternative Jobcentre locations, taking into account access to public transport. The equality analysis and public consultation will help establish people’s ability to access services from alternative Jobcentre locations.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-11T16:59:45.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669132/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669132/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669132/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-06","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the effect of local public transport networks on people's ability to access alternative jobcentres in the event that Jobcentre Plus office closures in Glasgow go ahead.","false","Biography information for Natalie McGarry","Glasgow East","Natalie McGarry","58707"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669133","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-11","<p>This information requested is not available and would incur disproportionate cost to provide.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","58693 ; 58715","2017-01-11T15:07:35.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669133/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669133/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669133/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-06","Employment and Support Allowance: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many claimants attending Bridgeton Jobcentre Plus are in receipt of employment and support allowance.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","58713"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669134","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-11","<p>The number of people with live Universal Credit claims at Bridgeton Jobcentre Plus office, as at November 2016, is 253 and can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/universal-credit-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/universal-credit-statistics</a>.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-11T15:18:15.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669134/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669134/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669134/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-06","Universal Credit: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many claimants attending Bridgeton Jobcentre Plus are in receipt of universal credit.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","58714"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669135","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-11","<p>This information requested is not available and would incur disproportionate cost to provide.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","58693 ; 58713","2017-01-11T15:07:35.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669135/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669135/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669135/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-06","Jobseeker's Allowance: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many claimants attending Bridgeton Jobcentre Plus are in receipt of jobseeker's allowance.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","58715"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669136","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-11","<p>The national living wage was introduced by this government on 1<sup>st</sup> April 2016 at the rate of £7.20 per hour and is applicable to those aged 25 and over. The national minimum wage is for those aged 16 and over. The national living wage is due to increase in April 2017 to £7.50 per hour.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The effect of a change in the level of the national living wage, on Jobseeker’s Allowance, will be to readjust the amount of benefit payable by the equivalent amount, after any appropriate disregards have been taken into account. The change due in April 2017 will have no effect on eligibility to Jobseeker’s Allowance.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","59000","2017-01-11T17:12:07.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669136/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669136/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669136/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-06","Living Wage: Children and Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what effect the recent reassessment of the national living wage has had on the eligibility of (a) an over 25-year old single person, (b) an over 25-year old couple, (c) a single person aged between 21 and 24, (d) a couple aged between 21 and 24, (e) a single person aged between 18 and 20, (f) a couple aged between 18 and 20, (g) a singe person under the age of 18 and (h) a couple under the ages of 18 to claim jobseeker's allowance for up to the quoted 16 hours.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","58681"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669137","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-11","<p>The Public Accounts Committee hearing into the NAO Value for Money Study into Benefit Sanctions was held 12/12/2016 following publication of the report on 30/11/2016. The Public Accounts Committee has not yet published their final report and recommendations. DWP will respond to this once it has been published.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-11T16:45:33.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669137/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669137/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669137/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-06","Social Security Benefits: Disqualification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when he plans to respond to the National Audit Office's report on Benefit Sanctions, published on 30 November 2016; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","58967"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669138","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-12","<p>We continually keep the assessment criteria for Personal Independence Payment and Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) under review.</p><p> </p><p>As announced on 1 October 2016, we will stop requiring people with the most severe, lifetime conditions to be repeatedly assessed for ESA and Universal Credit. Over the coming months we will work with our health assessment provider, medical professionals and other stakeholders to develop a set of criteria to switch off re-assessments for people with the most severe health conditions or disabilities.</p><p> </p><p>In addition the Green Paper, launched on 31 October 2016 explores a range of options, and points to long-term reform, including how we might simplify and improve the assessment process for people with health conditions.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-01-12T16:35:39.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669138/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669138/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669138/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-06","Social Security Benefits: Medical Examinations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether he plans to change testing criteria for (a) personal independence payments and (b) employment and support allowance.","false","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","East Devon","Sir Hugo Swire","58957"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669139","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-16","<p>There is currently interim support available during the appeals period. For those who were members of the Motability scheme under DLA, Motability pays for a £175 million package of transitional support which normally includes a £2,000 cash lump sum. Individuals could use this payment to support their mobility needs during this time.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is always exploring new ways to support disabled people, including those making PIP appeals. There have been no decisions at this time.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-01-16T13:12:06.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669139/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669139/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669139/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-06","Personal Independence Payment: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether he plans to put in place greater interim and transitional funding for claimants (a) during and (b) after personal independence payment appeals.","false","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","East Devon","Sir Hugo Swire","58958"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669140","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-16","<p>We regularly review the way in which we process personal independence payments (PIP) and employment and support allowance (ESA) to ensure claimants are paid at the earliest opportunity. PIP has an on-going continuous improvement plan in place. Identifying opportunities for claimants to provide the ‘right’ evidence at the ‘right’ time, enhancing the quality of the decision making process.</p><p> </p><p>Where the claimant has not provided all the information required to determine their award we proactively seek this information from them or a third party.</p><p> </p><p>Once an award for ESA has been made we select the quickest method of payment available to ensure that any payment due is paid to the claimant as quickly as possible. For the majority of new claimants to PIP they will be paid any arrears of benefit within a few days of the decision being made.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-01-16T13:06:35.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669140/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669140/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669140/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-06","Social Security Benefits: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps he is taking to reduce the time taken to make payments for (a) personal independence payments and (b) employment and support allowance.","false","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","East Devon","Sir Hugo Swire","58956"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669141","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-11","<p>Expenditure for the Work Choice Programme for the years requested was £117.8m for 2014-15, of which £87.5m was paid to suppliers and £30.3m grant-in-aid to Remploy, and £124.4m for 2015-16.</p><p> </p><p>We previously excluded the Remploy 2014-15 figure from Work Choice expenditure figures as they were then a public sector arm’s length body, funded by grant in aid rather than through a commercial contract. Since transferring to private ownership, Remploy was awarded a commercial Work Choice contract for which expenditure was £40.8m in 2015/16. This figure is included in the £124.4m of Work Choice spending for 2015-16.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-11T17:43:28.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669141/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669141/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669141/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-06","Employment Schemes: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the Answers of 24 February 2014, Official Report, column 5W, what the expenditure for the Work Choice programme was in (a) 2014-15 and (b) 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","58964"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669142","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-16","<p>The Department for Work &amp; Pensions (DWP) operates a proof of life programme (referred to as a Life Certificate) where State Pension customers residing permanently outside the United Kingdom are required to provide independent evidence, in the form of a witness statement, confirming that they are alive. The Life Certificate also provides verification of a customer’s address and contact telephone number and forms an integral part of DWP’s strategy to reduce fraud and error by ensuring that State Pension is paid to the right person at the right time. In addition to the Life Certificate, DWP has agreements in place with some countries to exchange data when a customer is deceased.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-01-16T14:24:50.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669142/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669142/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669142/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-06","State Retirement Pensions: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 2 November 2016 to Question 50587, on state retirement pensions, by what means overseas claimants are audited.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","58970"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669143","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-16","<p>The available data on clearances of claims by type (i.e. awarded, disallowed or withdrawn) to Personal Independence Payment (PIP), by a range of breakdowns including whether they were new claimants or Disability Living Allowance to PIP reassessment claimants, is available from Stat-Xplore: <a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/</a>. Guidance on how to use Stat-Xplore can be found here: <a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/index.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/index.html</a></p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","58973","2017-01-16T14:18:10.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669143/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669143/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669143/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-06","Personal Independence Payment: Older People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many recipients of disability living allowance have undertaken a reassessment for personal independence payments when over the age of 65 since April 2013.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","58972"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669144","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-16","<p>The available data on clearances of claims by type (i.e. awarded, disallowed or withdrawn) to Personal Independence Payment (PIP), by a range of breakdowns including whether they were new claimants or Disability Living Allowance to PIP reassessment claimants, is available from Stat-Xplore: <a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/</a>. Guidance on how to use Stat-Xplore can be found here: <a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/index.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/index.html</a></p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","58972","2017-01-16T14:18:10.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669144/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669144/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669144/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-06","Personal Independence Payment: Older People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many recipients of disability living allowance who were reassessed for personal independence payments when over the age of 65 have had their claim disallowed since April 2013.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","58973"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669145","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-23","<p>This information requested is not held centrally. Published national statistics on the Personal Independence Payment is available on gov.uk.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-01-23T10:48:32.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669145/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669145/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669145/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-06","Personal Independence Payment: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many unsuccessful applications for personal independence payments were appealed in 2016; and what proportion of those appeals were (a) ruled in favour of the appellant and (b) upheld by the tribunal.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","58999"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669146","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-11","<p>There are separate ESIF Operational Programmes in place for the European Regional Development Fund (ERDF) and the European Social Fund (ESF) in England and the emphasis for both programmes for the 2014-2020 programme is to ensure funds support local growth. Funds are allocated to Local Enterprise Partnership (LEP) areas to increase impact of other local public and private investments, such as the Local Growth Fund.</p><p> </p><p>The ESF Operational Programme issued in September 2015, deliberately does not refer to the Gypsy, Roma and Traveller community as a specific target group. ESF operates on a principle of equality and inclusion and it is not considered appropriate to set aside allocations for specific groups on the grounds of ethnic origin, religion, gender or disability.</p><p> </p><p>LEPs have put forward plans/approaches to deliver against the themes of the ESF Operational Programme. Members of the Gypsy, Roma and Traveller community could benefit from support across the different priorities, and Investment Priority 1.4 in particular includes the facility to support marginalised individuals and people with complex barriers.</p><p> </p><p>Gypsy, Roma and Traveller groups have been encouraged to engage with LEPs with a view to ensuring they are included in local partnerships and have the opportunity to influence local calls and we are also in the process of writing to LEPs to encourage them to work closely with Gypsy, Roma and Traveller representatives.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-01-11T17:07:30.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669146/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669146/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669146/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-06","Employment Schemes: Travellers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will amend the Operational Guidance issued to local enterprise partnerships in September 2014 on the allocation of European Structural and Investment Funds (ESIF), to indicate that ESIF and resources should be used to support greater access to adult education, skills training and the labour market for Gypsy, Roma and Traveller groups.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","58986"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669147","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-11","<p>The national living wage was introduced by this government on 1<sup>st</sup> April 2016 at the rate of £7.20 per hour and is applicable to those aged 25 and over. The national minimum wage is for those aged 16 and over. The national living wage is due to increase in April 2017 to £7.50 per hour.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The effect of a change in the level of the national living wage, on Jobseeker’s Allowance, will be to readjust the amount of benefit payable by the equivalent amount, after any appropriate disregards have been taken into account. The change due in April 2017 will have no effect on eligibility to Jobseeker’s Allowance.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","58681","2017-01-11T17:12:07.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669147/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669147/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669147/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-06","Jobseeker's Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of the reassessment of the national living wage on the eligibility to claim jobseeker's allowance to his Department's quoted up to 16 hours for (a) a single person aged over 25, (b) an old couple aged over 25, (c) a single person aged between 21 and 24, (d) a couple aged between 21 and 24, (e) a single person aged between 18 and 20, (f) a couple aged between 18 and 20, (g) a single person under the age of 18 and (h) a couple under the age of 18.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","59000"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669148","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-16","<p>The requested information will require some time to collate. I will write to the hon. Member with the requested information and place a copy of my response in the House library.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-01-16T16:39:47.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669148/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669148/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669148/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-06","Minimum Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 17 December 2016 to Question 55486, how many of the 687 employers named by his Department for non-compliance with the national minimum wage under the naming and shaming scheme have identified further arrears not included in the sum of arrears for which they were named under the self-correction mechanism; what the total was of those further self-corrected arrears; and to how many workers those further self-corrected arrears were owed.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","58981"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669149","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-11","<p>One hundred and sixty eight warning letters and 60 financial penalty notices have been issued to date by the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy to respondent employers under section 150 of the Small Business, Enterprise and Employment Act 2015 for failure to pay an employment tribunal award.</p><p>Financial penalties go to the Government. One financial penalty has been paid and 46 remain unpaid. The Department has recovered £98,667.53 in unpaid awards for claimants following the issuing of a warning letter only. An additional £750 unpaid award for a claimant was recovered as a result of the issuing of a warning letter and subsequently a financial penalty notice.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-01-11T11:07:28.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669149/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669149/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669149/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-06","Employment Tribunals Service: Fines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 7 September 2016 to Question 44543, how many (a) warning notices and (b) financial penalties have been issued to respondent employers to date under section 150 of the Small Business, Enterprise and Employment Act 2015 for failure to pay an employment tribunal award; how many of those financial penalties (i) have been paid and (ii) remain unpaid; and how much in previously unpaid awards has been recovered by his Department following (A) the issuing of a warning notice only and (B) the issuing of both a warning notice and a financial penalty.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","58968"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669150","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-11","<p>Eighteen financial penalties have been imposed to date on respondent employers for aggravated breach of employment law under section 16 of the Enterprise and Regulatory Reform Act 2013. Of these, 12 penalties have been paid. 2 penalties were unrecoverable due to the companies being either dissolved or liquidated. 4 remain unpaid and continue to be pursued. The total sum paid in financial penalties is £17,704.17.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-01-11T11:08:43.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669150/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669150/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669150/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-06","Employment Tribunals Service: Fines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 9 September 2016 to Question 44542, how many financial penalties have been imposed to date on respondent employers for aggravated breach of employment law under section 16 of the Enterprise and Regulatory Reform Act 2013; how many such penalties (a) have been paid and (b) remain unpaid; and what the total sum paid in penalties is.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","58969"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669151","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-11","The Government is committed to transferring the functions of relevant reserved tribunals to Scotland under the process set out in the Scotland Act 2016 and my officials are working closely with officials from the Scottish Government to develop the detailed plans to do so. Both the Minister for Small Business, Consumer and Corporate Responsibility at BEIS and I have recently corresponded with Ministers in the Scottish Government, on this matter.","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-01-11T17:21:38.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669151/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669151/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669151/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-06","Tribunals: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what recent discussions she has had with Ministers of the Scottish Government on the progress of devolving administrative responsibilities for (a) employment tribunals and (b) other relevant tribunals to the Scottish Government.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","58712"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669152","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-13","<p>The Government is considering the findings and recommendations made in the report ‘Lowest Cost Decarbonisation for the UK: the critical role of carbon capture and storage’, published by Parliamentary Advisory Group on Carbon Capture and Storage, and will set out its approach to carbon capture and storage in due course.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-01-13T11:08:55.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669152/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669152/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669152/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-06","Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will publish a response to the report published by the Parliamentary Advisory Group on Carbon Capture and Storage prior to the publication of the Government's emissions reduction plan.","false","Biography information for Callum McCaig","Aberdeen South","Callum McCaig","58702"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669153","Cabinet Office","false","2017-01-16","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-01-16T14:18:13.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669153/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669153/answer","Pat McFadden MP v.04 (002).pdf","UKSA Letter to Member - EU Nationals","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669153/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-01-06","Employment: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate his Department has made of the number of EU nationals working in each sector of the UK economy.","false","Biography information for Mr Pat McFadden","Wolverhampton South East","Mr Pat McFadden","58686"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669154","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-11","<p>The Strike Price comparator for Hinkley Point C is the HPC Strike Price; this is £92.50/MWh (2012 prices), which is reduced to £89.50/MWh (2012 prices) if a final investment decision on Sizewell C is reached.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-01-11T11:40:51.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669154/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669154/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669154/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-06","Wind Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 16 December 2016 to Question 57518, what the strike price comparator is for Hinkley Point C.","false","Biography information for Callum McCaig","Aberdeen South","Callum McCaig","58725"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669155","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-11","<p>The various costs associated with electricity generation that make up each Strike Price comparator are set out in the BEIS Electricity Generation Cost report published November 2016.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-01-11T11:40:00.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669155/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669155/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669155/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-06","Wind Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 16 December 2016 to Question 57518, if his Department will publish the methodology used to calculate strike price comparators for renewable energy technologies.","false","Biography information for Callum McCaig","Aberdeen South","Callum McCaig","58726"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669156","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-01-12","<p>This is a matter for Ofcom. DCMS has noted Ofcom's competition and consumer assessment, as set out in its successive consultations on the forthcoming auction of 2.3 and 3.4 GHz spectrum.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","58744","2017-01-12T17:47:18.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669156/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669156/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669156/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-01-06","Mobile Phones: Radio Frequencies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment her Department has made of the correlation between prices in the mobile phones market and the uneven distribution of mobile spectrum.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","58746"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669157","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-11","<p>We do not currently hold data on individual firms. However, we do hold information on the number of contracts awarded under the scheme.</p><p>Firms are awarded Small Business Research Initiative (SBRI) funding through contracts on a competitive basis in two phases:</p><p>(i) Phase 1, which typically provides up to £100,000 for companies to test the feasibility of their ideas;</p><p>(ii) Phase 2, which typically provides up to £1,000,000 for companies to develop a prototype or demonstrator.</p><p>The details of Phase 1 and Phase 2 SBRI contracts awarded are below:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2009/10</p></td><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>2015/16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Phase 1</p></td><td><p>340</p></td><td><p>164</p></td><td><p>246</p></td><td><p>313</p></td><td><p>327</p></td><td><p>418</p></td><td><p>268</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Phase 2</p></td><td><p>93</p></td><td><p>21</p></td><td><p>28</p></td><td><p>106</p></td><td><p>55</p></td><td><p>96</p></td><td><p>55</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>On 21 November, my right hon. Friend the Prime Minister announced that she had asked David Connell from the Centre for Business Research at the Cambridge Judge Business School to review the Small Business Research Initiative.</p><p>The review is examining how we can maximise the impact of the SBRI programme to improve procurement outcomes for government, support and stimulate innovation by SMEs.</p><p>The review will report in spring this year.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","58786 ; 58787","2017-01-11T14:31:03.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669157/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669157/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669157/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-06","Small Business Research Initiative","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the (a) increase in sales, (b) additional investment attracted, (c) creation of jobs and (d) creation of intellectual property resulting from the work of the Small Business Research Initiative in each year since that body was established.","false","Biography information for Mr Iain Wright","Hartlepool","Mr Iain Wright","58785"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669158","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-01-16","<p>The government is committed to ensuring that the UK has a thriving digital economy throughout the country, including coastal towns such as Eastbourne.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-01-16T16:56:09.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669158/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669158/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669158/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-01-06","Digital Technology: Eastbourne","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps her Department is taking to support and further develop tech and digital industries in coastal areas such as Eastbourne.","false","Biography information for Caroline Ansell","Eastbourne","Caroline Ansell","58777"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669159","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-11","<p>We do not currently hold data on individual firms. However, we do hold information on the number of contracts awarded under the scheme.</p><p>Firms are awarded Small Business Research Initiative (SBRI) funding through contracts on a competitive basis in two phases:</p><p>(i) Phase 1, which typically provides up to £100,000 for companies to test the feasibility of their ideas;</p><p>(ii) Phase 2, which typically provides up to £1,000,000 for companies to develop a prototype or demonstrator.</p><p>The details of Phase 1 and Phase 2 SBRI contracts awarded are below:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2009/10</p></td><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>2015/16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Phase 1</p></td><td><p>340</p></td><td><p>164</p></td><td><p>246</p></td><td><p>313</p></td><td><p>327</p></td><td><p>418</p></td><td><p>268</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Phase 2</p></td><td><p>93</p></td><td><p>21</p></td><td><p>28</p></td><td><p>106</p></td><td><p>55</p></td><td><p>96</p></td><td><p>55</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>On 21 November, my right hon. Friend the Prime Minister announced that she had asked David Connell from the Centre for Business Research at the Cambridge Judge Business School to review the Small Business Research Initiative.</p><p>The review is examining how we can maximise the impact of the SBRI programme to improve procurement outcomes for government, support and stimulate innovation by SMEs.</p><p>The review will report in spring this year.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","58785 ; 58787","2017-01-11T14:31:03.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669159/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669159/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669159/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-06","Small Business Research Initiative","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many firms have received funding through the Small Business Research Initiative to (a) test an idea and (b) develop a prototype in each year since that body was established.","false","Biography information for Mr Iain Wright","Hartlepool","Mr Iain Wright","58786"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669160","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-11","<p>We do not currently hold data on individual firms. However, we do hold information on the number of contracts awarded under the scheme.</p><p>Firms are awarded Small Business Research Initiative (SBRI) funding through contracts on a competitive basis in two phases:</p><p>(i) Phase 1, which typically provides up to £100,000 for companies to test the feasibility of their ideas;</p><p>(ii) Phase 2, which typically provides up to £1,000,000 for companies to develop a prototype or demonstrator.</p><p>The details of Phase 1 and Phase 2 SBRI contracts awarded are below:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2009/10</p></td><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>2015/16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Phase 1</p></td><td><p>340</p></td><td><p>164</p></td><td><p>246</p></td><td><p>313</p></td><td><p>327</p></td><td><p>418</p></td><td><p>268</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Phase 2</p></td><td><p>93</p></td><td><p>21</p></td><td><p>28</p></td><td><p>106</p></td><td><p>55</p></td><td><p>96</p></td><td><p>55</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>On 21 November, my right hon. Friend the Prime Minister announced that she had asked David Connell from the Centre for Business Research at the Cambridge Judge Business School to review the Small Business Research Initiative.</p><p>The review is examining how we can maximise the impact of the SBRI programme to improve procurement outcomes for government, support and stimulate innovation by SMEs.</p><p>The review will report in spring this year.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","58785 ; 58786","2017-01-11T14:31:03.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669160/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669160/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669160/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-06","Small Business Research Initiative: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of the Small Business Research Initiative; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Iain Wright","Hartlepool","Mr Iain Wright","58787"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669161","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-11","<p>The Government recognises the significant contribution made by charitable funders of research. The charity support element of Quality Related research funding, provided by the Higher Education Funding Council for England (HEFCE), recognises the public benefit arising from research funded by charities. Over the period 2011-17, HEFCE has protected support for institutions leveraging funding from the charitable sector and has provided £198m per annum for this through to 2016-17.</p><p>The “Allocation of Science and Research funding 2016 – 2020” confirmed the Government’s expectation that throughout this period HEFCE should continue to incentivise Higher Education Institutes (HEIs) to work with businesses and charities, leveraging additional investment. It will be for the HEFCE Board to determine how much to provide for charity research support from within their overall research allocation for 2017-18, once they have received their annual Grant Letter from Ministers.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-01-11T15:18:45.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669161/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669161/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669161/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-06","Charity Research Support Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what consideration has been given to supporting charity investment in universities through increasing investment in the Charity Research Support Fund.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","58794"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669162","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-16","<p>We expect to appoint the Commissioner in 2017 and we are completing the rest of the implementation in parallel. This includes consulting on, preparing and laying secondary legislation on the Commissioner’s complaints handling function. Our public consultation on these Regulations closed in December and we are preparing the Government Response. Work is also ongoing to setup the Commissioner’s office and create a web presence.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-01-16T09:47:26.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669162/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669162/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669162/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-06","Small Business Commissioner","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what progress has been made on establishing and appointing a Small Business Commissioner under the Enterprise Act 2016; and what the timescale is for the appointment of that Commissioner.","false","Biography information for Mr Iain Wright","Hartlepool","Mr Iain Wright","58788"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669163","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-11","<p>The Government is committed to maintain and enhance the strength of our research base. This is why we have protected the science resource budget in real terms from its 2015/16 level of £4.7 billion for the rest of the parliament, as well as committing to invest in new scientific infrastructure on a record scale – £6.9 billion over the period 2015- 21.</p><p>We are introducing a new Global Challenges Research Fund of £1.5 billion over the Spending Review period to support research on global issues affecting developing countries. The Newton Fund will also be doubled to £150 million a year by 2021.</p><p>At Autumn Statement 2016 we announced that we will make Britain the global go-to nation for scientists, innovators and tech investors, by investing an extra £2 billion a year in R&amp;D by 2020/21. We are committed to ensure that the UK continues to be a world leader in international science, including biomedical research.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-01-11T15:19:36.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669163/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669163/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669163/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-06","Medicine: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what incentives the Government provides to support biomedical research into the most deadly global diseases.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","58902"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669164","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-16","<p>There have been no director disqualifications in relation to convictions abroad under section 104 of the Small Business, Enterprise and Employment Act 2015</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-01-16T14:21:11.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669164/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669164/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669164/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-06","Directors: Disqualification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many director disqualifications in relation to convictions abroad there have been under section 104 of the Small Business, Enterprise and Employment Act 2015.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","58879"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669165","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-11","<p>The table below gives the amount of coal which the UK exported in the last 10 years:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>UK Coal Exports (thousand tonnes)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006</p></td><td><p>443</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007</p></td><td><p>544</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008</p></td><td><p>599</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009</p></td><td><p>646</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>715</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>491</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>488</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>593</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>425</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>385</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>5,331</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><em>Source: Table DUKES 2.4 Digest of UK Energy Statistics, July 2016, available at:</em></p><p><em><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/solid-fuels-and-derived-gases-chapter-2-digest-of-united-kingdom-energy-statistics-dukes" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/solid-fuels-and-derived-gases-chapter-2-digest-of-united-kingdom-energy-statistics-dukes</a></em></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-01-11T11:41:47.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669165/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669165/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669165/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-06","Coal: Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many tonnes of coal the UK has exported in the last 10 years; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","58933"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669166","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-16","<p>There have been no convictions for general false statement offences under the section referred to since 1<sup>st</sup> January 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-01-16T14:32:26.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669166/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669166/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669166/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-06","Companies Act 2006","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many convictions there have been for general false statement offences under section 1112 of the Companies Act 2006 since 1 January 2015.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","58808"
