"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669170","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-16","<p>Six people (equating to six full-time equivalents) work for the Breaches Team at Companies House.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-01-16T14:33:50.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669170/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669170/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669170/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-06","Companies House: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many people work for the breaches team at Companies House (a) in total and (b) as full-time equivalents.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","58846"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669171","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-11","<p>When a company that is actively trading does not have a natural director (a director who is an individual rather than a corporate body), Companies House will (on behalf of the Secretary of State) issue a direction requiring the company to appoint one. Companies House's primary aim will be to try to achieve compliance. If the company does not comply, the case will be referred to prosecutors and a prosecution will be bought if it is deemed to be in the public interest. In the event of a conviction the Court would impose the appropriate penalty. However, to date, all companies have either complied with the direction issued by Companies House or prosecution action has not been in the public interest as defined in the Code for Crown Prosecutors.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-01-11T17:09:40.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669171/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669171/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669171/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-06","Companies Act 2006","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many financial penalties have been awarded in relation to the direction requiring a company to make appointment under section 156(6) of the Companies Act 2006 since 1 January 2015.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","58838"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669172","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-16","<p>No company officers or Limited Liability Partnership designated members have been fined under the sections referred to since 31<sup>st</sup> January 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-01-16T14:35:13.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669172/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669172/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669172/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-06","Company, Limited Liability Partnership and Business (Names and Trading Disclosures) Regulations 2015","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many company officers and Limited Liability Partnership designated members have been fined for offences under sections 21, 22 and 23 of the Company, Limited Liability Partnership and Business (Names and Trading Disclosures) Regulations 2015 since 31 January 2015.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","58847"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669173","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-11","<p>Since 1<sup>st</sup> January 2015 no financial penalties have been awarded in relation to the register of directors under the section referred to.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-01-11T17:10:19.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669173/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669173/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669173/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-06","Companies Act 2006","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many financial penalties have been awarded in relation to the register of directors under section 162(6) of the Companies Act 2006 since 1 January 2015.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","58839"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669174","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-16","<p>The total value of fines collected since 31<sup>st</sup> January 2015 for companies’ officers’ offences under the sections referred to is nil.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-01-16T14:37:33.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669174/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669174/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669174/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-06","Company, Limited Liability Partnership and Business (Names and Trading Disclosures) Regulations 2015","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what the total value is of fines collected for companies officers' offences under sections 21, 22 and 23 of the Company, Limited Liability Partnership and Business (Names and Trading Disclosures) Regulations 2015 since 31 January 2015.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","58848"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669175","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-16","<p>The total value of fines collected since 31<sup>st</sup> January 2015 for companies’ officers’ offences under the sections referred to is nil.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-01-16T14:36:01.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669175/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669175/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669175/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-06","Company, Limited Liability Partnership and Business (Names and Trading Disclosures) Regulations 2015","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what the total value is of fines for companies' offences under sections 21, 22 and 23 of the Company, Limited Liability Partnership and Business (Names and Trading Disclosures) Regulations 2015 since 31 January 2015.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","58852"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669176","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-16","<p>Enforcement of Section 21, 22 and 23 of the Company Limited Liability Partnership and Business (Names and Trading Disclosures) Regulations is undertaken in response to information being brought to the attention of Companies House or another enforcement agencies attention, rather than through pro-active enforcement visits. Companies House's primary aim will be to try to achieve compliance. If the company does not comply, the case will be referred to prosecutors and a prosecution will be bought if it is deemed to be in the public interest. In the event of a conviction the Court would impose the appropriate penalty. Companies House has received two complaints under these sections. Of these two complied when contacted by Companies House and one company was on a dissolution path and so no further action was taken as it would not have been in the public interest as defined in the Code for Crown Prosecutors.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-01-16T14:31:38.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669176/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669176/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669176/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-06","Company, Limited Liability Partnership and Business (Names and Trading Disclosures) Regulations 2015","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many registered offices, inspection places and business locations the Companies House Breaches Team has visited in order to verify companies' compliance with sections 21, 22 and 23 of the Company, Limited Liability Partnership and Business (Names and Trading Disclosures) Regulations 2015 since 31 January 2015.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","58853"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669177","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-16","<p>There are 4,086,190 registered offices and inspection locations in relation to sections 21, 22, and 23 of the Company, Limited Liability Partnership and Business (Names and Trading Disclosures) Regulations 2006.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-01-16T14:38:22.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669177/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669177/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669177/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-06","Company, Limited Liability Partnership and Business (Names and Trading Disclosures) Regulations 2015","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many registered offices and inspection places there are in relation to sections 21, 22 and 23 of the Company, Limited Liability Partnership and Business (Names and Trading Disclosures) Regulations 2015.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","58850"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669178","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-16","<p>No companies have been fined for offences under the sections referred to since 31<sup>st</sup> January 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-01-16T14:39:09.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669178/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669178/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669178/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-06","Company, Limited Liability Partnership and Business (Names and Trading Disclosures) Regulations 2015","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many companies have been fined for offences under sections 21, 22 and 23 of the Company, Limited Liability Partnership and Business (Names and Trading Disclosures) Regulations 2015 since 31 January 2015.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","58851"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669179","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-16","<p>Companies House’s Breaches Team does not monitor for breaches of sections 21, 22, and 23 of the Company, Limited Liability Partnership and Business (Names and Trading Disclosures) Regulations 2015. It acts on receipt of a public complaint and during the period Companies House received three complaints.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-01-16T14:39:57.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669179/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669179/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669179/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-06","Company, Limited Liability Partnership and Business (Names and Trading Disclosures) Regulations 2015","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many non-dormant UK companies and Limited Liability Partnerships Companies House Breaches Team monitors for breaches of sections 21, 22 and 23 of the Company, Limited Liability Partnership and Business (Names and Trading Disclosures) Regulations 2015.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","58849"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669180","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-01-16","<p>Our international standing is highly important - not only to inbound tourism but in wider trade terms. Currently the UK government is not considering membership of the World Tourism Organisation but it is an organisation we remain in contact with to ensure the UK is participating fully in international tourism discussions<strong>. </strong></p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-01-16T13:15:21.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669180/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669180/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669180/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-01-06","World Tourism Organisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, for what reasons the Government has not joined the World Tourism Organisation.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","58871"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669181","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-16","<p>Companies House received three public complaints surrounding sections 21, 22, and 23 of the Company, Limited Liability Partnership and Business (Names and Trading Disclosures) Regulations 2015. Of these complaints two complied when contacted by Companies House and one company was on a dissolution path and so no further action was taken as it would not have been in the public interest as defined in the Code for Crown Prosecutors.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-01-16T14:42:10.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669181/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669181/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669181/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-06","Company, Limited Liability Partnership and Business (Names and Trading Disclosures) Regulations 2015","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many companies the Companies House Breaches Team has investigated for breaches of sections 21, 22 and 23 of the Company, Limited Liability Partnership and Business (Names and Trading Disclosures) Regulations 2015 since 31 January 2015.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","58854"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669182","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-16","<p>No companies have been found guilty of offences under the sections referred to since 31<sup>st</sup> January 2015</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-01-16T14:41:01.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669182/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669182/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669182/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-06","Company, Limited Liability Partnership and Business (Names and Trading Disclosures) Regulations 2015","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many companies have been found guilty of offences under sections 21, 22 and 23 of the Company, Limited Liability Partnership and Business (Names and Trading Disclosures) Regulations 2015.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","58855"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669183","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-11","<p>During the period the Court imposed 4,701 fines on companies in relation to failure deliver annual returns under section 858(1) of the Companies Act 2006. The total value of the fines levied was £671,906</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-01-11T14:15:10.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669183/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669183/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669183/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-06","Companies Act 2006","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many financial penalties have been awarded in relation to failure to deliver annual returns under section 858(1) of the Companies Act 2006 since 1 January 2015.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","58841"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669184","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-11","<p>Since 1<sup>st</sup> January 2015, no financial penalties have been awarded in relation to the section referred to.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-01-11T17:12:18.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669184/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669184/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669184/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-01-06","Companies Act 2006","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many financial penalties have been awarded in relation to duty to notify registrars of changes under section 167(4) of the Companies Act 2006 since 1 January 2015.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","58840"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669185","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-11","<p>The most recent notification for the EU domestic support in agriculture is for the marketing year 2012/13.</p><p> </p><p>The total aggregate measure of support notified was €5.9bn. This is overwhelmingly market price support which is only calculated for the EU as a whole and not for individual member states. The products with the largest notified support are:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Product</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Aggregate Measure of Support</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Butter</p></td><td><p>€2,743m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Common wheat</p></td><td><p>€1,865m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Skimmed milk powder</p></td><td><p>€1,145m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Wine</p></td><td><p>€696m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Milk</p></td><td><p>€192m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Ethyl alcohol</p></td><td><p>€82m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Sugar</p></td><td><p>€59m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Bee keeping</p></td><td><p>€43m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Olive oil</p></td><td><p>€18m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Fibre flax and hemp</p></td><td><p>€7m</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-01-11T12:48:50.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669185/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669185/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669185/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-06","EU Trade: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what the 10 largest domestic subsidies used by UK industry by virtue of UK membership of EU trading arrangements under the World Trade Organisation definition of aggregate measurement of support are by (a) type of good, (b) sector, (c) quantity of goods affected and (d) estimated value to the UK economy.","false","Biography information for Mr Chris Leslie","Nottingham East","Chris Leslie","58912"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669186","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-11","<p>The EU currently notifies over 120 tariff rate quotas in agriculture and a further 19 non-agriculture tariff rate quotas. There can be several tariff rate quotas within a single sector such as beef or sugar, for different products and different countries which export to the EU and UK. We do not currently assess tariff rate quotas by economic value: they are defined and administered according to the volume rather than the value of imports. All tariff rate quotas which other countries use to export to the UK, however, will be important to them, and important to the industry affected.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-01-11T12:51:43.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669186/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669186/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669186/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-06","EU Trade: Import Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what the 10 existing EU tariff rate quotas with the largest economic value for the UK economy are by (a) type of good, (b) sector of the economy, (c) quantity and (d) estimated value for UK industry.","false","Biography information for Mr Chris Leslie","Nottingham East","Chris Leslie","58913"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669187","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-11","<p>In leaving the EU, we will need to update the terms of our WTO membership where, at present, our commitments are currently contained in the EU’s schedule. We recognise the need to work with the EU and with other WTO Members in order to ensure a smooth transition which minimises the disruption to our trading relationships with other WTO Members, including developing country Members and our closest trading partners.</p><p> </p><p>As the Secretary of State for International Trade said in his Written Ministerial Statement on 5<sup>th</sup> December “the Government will prepare the necessary draft schedules which replicate as far as possible our current obligations”. We do not intend to alter the scope of concessions currently enjoyed by WTO members. While this is largely a technical process, there are a number of areas where we will need to consult with other WTO members.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","58910","2017-01-11T12:42:54.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669187/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669187/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669187/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-06","EU Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of whether the UK should negotiate a UK-specific entitlement to the aggregate measurement of support that the EU is allowed under World Trade Organisation rules; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Chris Leslie","Nottingham East","Chris Leslie","58911"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669188","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-11","<p>In leaving the EU, we will need to update the terms of our WTO membership where, at present, our commitments are currently contained in the EU’s schedule. We recognise the need to work with the EU and with other WTO Members in order to ensure a smooth transition which minimises the disruption to our trading relationships with other WTO Members, including developing country Members and our closest trading partners.</p><p> </p><p>As the Secretary of State for International Trade said in his Written Ministerial Statement on 5<sup>th</sup> December “the Government will prepare the necessary draft schedules which replicate as far as possible our current obligations”. We do not intend to alter the scope of concessions currently enjoyed by WTO members. While this is largely a technical process, there are a number of areas where we will need to consult with other WTO members.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","58911","2017-01-11T12:42:54.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669188/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669188/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669188/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-06","EU Trade: Import Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of whether the UK should agree a division of EU tariff rate quotas before consideration by Parliament of UK-specific World Trade Organisation schedules of concessions; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Chris Leslie","Nottingham East","Chris Leslie","58910"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669189","Department for International Trade","false","2017-01-16","<p>The Department for International Trade assumed the responsibilities of UKTI in July 2016.</p><p> </p><p>A yearly client survey of businesses supported by DIT is undertaken by the International Trade and Investment team to measure quality of service and reported impact which includes the Events Alliance Programme. Latest figures available cover support provided in 2015-16:</p><p> </p><ul><li>For those attending DIT-sponsored Events, on average, businesses anticipated additional export sales of £611,000 per business as a result of attending events organised with the support of the Department.</li></ul><p> </p><ul><li>Event satisfaction was 74% among businesses supported.</li></ul>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-01-16T17:57:18.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669189/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669189/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669189/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-01-06","UK Trade and Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what value for money assessment his Department has made of the UKTI Events Alliance programme.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","58684"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669190","Department for International Trade","false","2017-01-16","<p>The Department for International Trade assumed the responsibilities of UKTI in July 2016.</p><p>Over the last 12 months an estimate of £127.7 million export wins has been recorded as outcomes from the leads generated by the Department for International Trade's Events Alliance programme.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-01-16T17:34:12.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669190/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669190/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669190/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-01-06","UK Trade and Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what the outcomes have been of the leads generated by the UKTI Events Alliance programme in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","58685"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669191","Department for International Trade","false","2017-01-16","<p>The Department for International Trade (DIT) is committed to opening up its contract opportunities to suppliers to ensure economies of scale, global reach, professionalism and operational efficiencies. DIT therefore outsources all event delivery (in which around 400 will be delivered globally in 2016-17). DIT’s incumbent supplier’s contract will end in 2017.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-01-16T17:48:48.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669191/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669191/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669191/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-01-06","Department for International Trade: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, with reference to contract notice 2016/5 166-299652, for what reasons his Department decided to tender for event specialists; and whether his Department considered using trade associations to deliver any of those events.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","58690"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669192","Department for International Trade","false","2017-01-13","<p>The UK believes in a free and open approach to trade. There was no formal vote.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-01-13T12:23:54.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669192/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669192/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669192/answer","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669192/answer/previousversion/29424","Biography information for Greg Hands","202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-01-06","Antidumping","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how the UK's representative on the Committee of Permanent Representatives was instructed to vote on the proposals to modernise the UK's trade defence instruments.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","58975"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669193","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-01-13","<p>All departments are equipping themselves with the resources they need to get the best deal for the UK. Recruitment is ongoing and we will not be giving a running commentary on particular groups. The Department for Exiting the European Union now has over 300 staff, plus the expertise of over 120 officials in Brussels from the UK Permanent Representation to the EU, and is growing fast.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","58942","2017-01-13T14:14:21.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669193/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669193/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669193/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-01-06","Department for Exiting the European Union: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many trade negotiators his Department has recruited since its creation.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","58943"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669194","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-01-13","<p>All departments are equipping themselves with the resources they need to get the best deal for the UK. Recruitment is ongoing and we will not be giving a running commentary on particular groups. The Department for Exiting the European Union now has over 300 staff, plus the expertise of over 120 officials in Brussels from the UK Permanent Representation to the EU, and is growing fast.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","58943","2017-01-13T14:14:21.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669194/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669194/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669194/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-01-06","Department for Exiting the European Union: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many staff with negotiation expertise his Department has recruited since June 2016.","false","Biography information for Roger Mullin","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Roger Mullin","58942"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669195","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-01-13","<p>DExEU officials, supported by officials across Government, are carrying out a programme of sectoral and regulatory analysis. We are conducting analysis on over 50 sectors within the areas of goods; services; financial services; network industries; and agriculture and fisheries. We are also carrying out analysis on cross-cutting regulations. Together with extensive stakeholder engagement all this analysis will be used to inform the Government’s approach to, and during, the negotiations. <br><br></p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-01-13T14:20:03.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669195/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669195/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669195/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-01-06","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, which 57 areas of sectoral analysis will feature in the negotiations that the Government is undertaking on the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr Pat McFadden","Wolverhampton South East","Mr Pat McFadden","58659"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669196","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-01-11","<p>We will set out our broad plans to Parliament and the public for scrutiny before triggering Article 50 by the end of next March, repeating the proviso as agreed by the House on 12 October 2016, without division, confirmed on the 7th December, that nothing we do or say should undermine the UK's negotiating position.<br><br></p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-01-11T16:32:29.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669196/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669196/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669196/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-01-06","Brexit: Publications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what the options are for the form in which the document containing the Government's plan for the UK leaving the EU will be published before Article 50 is triggered.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","58758"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669197","Department for Education","false","2017-01-18","<p>The Universities and Colleges Admissions Service (UCAS) publishes data on applicants, applications and acceptances to full-time undergraduate courses.</p><p>There were 19,210 applicants to medicine courses in total with a 15 October 2017 UCAS deadline, 4% fewer (-890 people) than last year.</p><p>The Department engages with higher education institutions on an on-going basis, across a range of issues.</p><p><strong>The tables show the number of applicants for medicine courses with a 15 October deadline (2017 cycle) in the UK<sup>1</sup>: </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Domicile of applicant</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2017</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>UK</p></td><td><p>17,000</p></td><td><p>17,140</p></td><td><p>15,220</p></td><td><p>14,820</p></td><td><p>14,450</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>All</p></td><td><p>22,130</p></td><td><p>22,740</p></td><td><p>20,390</p></td><td><p>20,100</p></td><td><p>19,210</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Difference between cycle and 2016 cycle</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2017</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>UK</p></td><td><p>15%</p></td><td><p>16%</p></td><td><p>3%</p></td><td><p>0%</p></td><td><p>-2%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>All</p></td><td><p>10%</p></td><td><p>13%</p></td><td><p>1%</p></td><td><p>0%</p></td><td><p>-4%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The number of applications to Medicine and Dentistry courses (subject Group A) by the 15 January UCAS deadline will be published on 2 February.</p><p>Notes:</p><p>1. The figures were extracted from the UCAS October 2017 Deadline Applicant Statistics available via the following weblink:</p><p><a href="https://www.ucas.com/corporate/news-and-key-documents/news/applicant-numbers-%E2%80%98early-deadline%E2%80%99-university-courses-increase" target="_blank">https://www.ucas.com/corporate/news-and-key-documents/news/applicant-numbers-%E2%80%98early-deadline%E2%80%99-university-courses-increase</a></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","58860","2017-01-18T17:02:35.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669197/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669197/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/669197/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-06","Medicine: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what discussions she has had with UK higher education institutions about the nine per cent drop in applications for medicine courses in UK universities for the 2017-18 academic year.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","58859"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663104","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","true","2017-01-05","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring there is no impunity for these heinous crimes committed by Daesh, as shown by the Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Boris Johnson)'s launching of the global campaign Bringing Daesh to Justice. As a first step in this campaign, we are working with the government of Iraq to bring a proposal before the UN on evidence gathering and preservation in Iraq. It is vital that this is done now, before evidence is lost or destroyed. This campaign is about justice for all Daesh victims and we expect it to cover all violations of international humanitarian law and violations and abuses of international human rights law by Daesh including war crimes, crimes against humanity and genocide.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-01-05T16:47:09.383Z","2017-01-06T13:56:42.707Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663104/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663104/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663104/answer",,"Lord Archer of Weston-Super-Mare","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663104/answer/previousversion/28631",,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-21","Islamic State: Crimes against Humanity","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the remarks by the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs on 20 April (HC Deb, col 996) concerning the gathering and preservation of evidence that could in future be used in a court to hold Daesh to account for its crimes against Shi’a and Sunni Muslims, Christians, Yazidis, Kurds and other groups, what steps they are taking to ensure that genocide committed against Christians is included in their proposals for the prosecution of Daesh.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL4319"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663105","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-09","<p>We are aware of a number of recent reports by human rights organisations, including Amnesty International, indicating that the Burmese military has used violence against the Rohingya during security operations in Rakhine since 9 October. We view these reports with deep concern. I raised our concerns when I visited Burma from 9-12 November, and urged Burmese Government Ministers to establish a full and independent investigation into human rights violations.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-01-09T15:11:40.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663105/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663105/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663105/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-21","Burma: Rohingya","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the findings on the use of violence by Myanmar security forces against Rohingya since 9 October, contained in the report from Amnesty International <i>We are at breaking point</i>.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL4320"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663106","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-09","<p>I have lobbied the government of Burma for an immediate resumption of humanitarian access to northern Rakhine State, and pressed for a full and independent investigation into all reports of human rights violations. The Burmese Government has committed to restore access and investigate allegations of violations. While we have seen a limited resumption of aid in some areas, in practice worrying restrictions on humanitarian access remain. Ministers from the Foreign and Commonwealth Office and the Department for International Development, as well as our Ambassador in Rangoon, continue to call on the Burmese Government and the military to restore access as a matter of urgency.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-01-09T15:12:24.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663106/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663106/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663106/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-21","Burma: Rohingya","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their response to the recommendations concerning (1) the cessation of violations of international law, and (2) the need for immediate unhindered access for human rights monitors and journalists, in northern Rakhine State, contained in the report from Amnesty International <i>We are at breaking point</i>.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL4321"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663107","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Government agrees there should be an independent investigation into allegations of human rights abuses perpetrated by the Burmese military during security operations in northern Rakhine State. I urged the Burmese Government to establish such an investigation when I visited Burma from 9-12 November. We note the creation of the Rakhine Investigation Commission, as well as concerns raised about its composition and impartiality. Now that the investigation is under way we call on the commission to demonstrate the commitments to impartiality made on its behalf by the Burmese Government.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-01-09T15:12:49.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663107/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663107/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663107/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-21","Burma: Rohingya","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their response to the recommendations concerning the initiation of an independent, impartial and effective investigation into alleged violations of international law in northern Rakhine State, contained in the report from Amnesty International <i>We are at breaking point</i>.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL4322"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663108","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-05","<p>The UK Government remains deeply concerned by the current situation in Rakhine and the persecution of the Muslim minority Rohingya community. The UK Government has repeatedly called on the Government of Bangladesh not to return the people seeking refuge back into danger and we continue to offer support through our work with the International Organization for Migration (IOM) and the World Food Programme. The UK is the largest provider of food aid to the 34,000 Rohingya refugees already living in official camps in Bangladesh. Since 2014 the UK has provided nearly £8 million to address the humanitarian suffering of Rohingya refugees and the vulnerable Bangladeshi communities that host them. UK-funded humanitarian programmes have benefitted 82,000 people in the south east of Bangladesh. Also in Bangladesh we are increasing access to nutrition, health and education services for refugees living in makeshift settlements and the host communities that support them.</p><p>The UK Government has also engaged the Government of Burma to urge a restrained security response, an independent investigation into allegations of human rights abuses, and for the immediate resumption of access for humanitarian aid. The Government of Burma has now committed to restoring humanitarian access and investigating allegations of human rights abuses. We will continue to monitor and support the delivery of these commitments.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-01-05T15:41:24.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663108/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663108/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663108/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-12-21","Burma: Rohingya","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps are being taken to provide assistance to the government of Bangladesh to help meet the humanitarian needs of Rohingya refugees from Myanmar.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL4323"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663109","Department of Health","false","2017-01-06","<p>Regulatory action in response to the findings in the reports has been taken forward by the Care Quality Commission. The Department continues to monitor the situation with particular regard being had to the statutory power of the Secretary of State to approve independent sector abortion providers to perform the termination of pregnancy under Section 1(3) of the Abortion Act 1967.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-01-06T13:57:14.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663109/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663109/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663109/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-21","Abortion","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what action they intend to take following the Care Quality Commission’s findings concerning Marie Stopes abortion clinics.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL4324"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663110","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-01","<p>There is no evidence at this stage that any warning or intelligence had been received indicating that there was an increased risk of serious active concerted indiscipline taking place at HMP Birmingham prior to the disturbance on 16 December.</p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State for Justice has ordered a full investigation into the disturbance at HMP Birmingham, which will be led by Sarah Payne, adviser to the independent Chief Inspector of Probation and former Director of the National Offender Management Service (NOMS) in Wales.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2017-02-01T12:02:10.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663110/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663110/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663110/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-21","Birmingham Prison","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the statement by Lord Keen of Elie on 19 December (HL Deb, cols 1530–1540) on the serious disturbance at HM Prison Birmingham, whether they had been warned two months previously of the risk of a riot, and if so, what action, if any, was taken to forestall it.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL4325"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663111","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-01","<p>The overall agreed Band 3 – 5 prison officer number for Berwyn when fully open is 438 which is part of the overall 8,000 we plan to recruit. This will be subject to on-going review once the prison is fully open.</p><p> </p><p>Prison Officer recruitment at HMP Berwyn has been ongoing since early 2015. We are on track to recruit the staff we need in readiness to open the prison next month.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2017-02-01T12:40:36.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663111/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663111/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663111/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-21","Berwyn Prison","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many prison officers they plan to recruit for the new HM Prison Wrexham; and whether this number is included in their estimate of 8000 officers to be recruited by 2018.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL4326"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663112","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-01","<p>We currently offer permanent flexible contracts to ex-prison officers under the HMPS Reserve Scheme which was established in November 2015. Under the HMPS Reserve Scheme, we offer a permanent flexible contract to prison officers who have left voluntarily within the preceding 2 years. These staff will work flexibly to meet the needs of the estate. This helps to support the current operational workforce across the estate and to complement existing methods for meeting the staffing needs of prisons around the country.</p><p> </p><p>HMPS Reserve staff provide a valuable flexible resource for NOMS by supporting prison regimes and as at 30 September 2016, the date of the most recent published figures, there were 10 prison officer reserves and they continue to be deployed on an on-going basis across the Service in support of existing staff including after the riot in HMP Birmingham.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2017-02-01T12:41:19.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663112/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663112/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663112/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-21","Prison Officers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many people are currently on the prison officer reserve list; what proportion of those on the reserve list have received training in the duties of a prison officer; and how many of those on the reserve list have been deployed to assist in prisons following the riot in HM Prison Birmingham.","false","Biography information for Lord Beith",,"Lord Beith","HL4327"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663113","Department for Education","false","2017-01-09","<p>In 2015, fewer countries performed significantly ahead of England than in 2012. In 2012, out of 65 participating countries, 10 performed significantly ahead of England in science, 19 in mathematics and 17 reading. In 2015, out of 70 countries, nine performed significantly ahead of England in science, 19 in mathematics and 14 in reading.</p><p> </p><p>The average performance of 15-year-olds in England, and the UK, has remained stable in each three-year cycle since 2006. As participating countries improve or decline, the performance of the UK relative to other countries has improved in science, moving from 21<sup>st</sup> to 15<sup>st</sup> position and has remained virtually unchanged in reading and mathematics.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2017-01-09T17:48:34.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663113/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663113/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663113/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-21","Schools: Standards","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Viscount Younger of Leckie on 20 December (HL4031), and following the Programme for International Student Assessment survey, whether they have made an assessment of the level of progress made by English schools since 2010 in closing the achievement gap with the world’s best performing countries.","false","Biography information for Lord Birt",,"Lord Birt","HL4328"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663114","Home Office","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Home Office does not monitor returnees after they have returned to their country of origin.</p><p>All returns to the Democratic Republic of Congo, including those persons who raise a protection claim, are considered on a case-by-case basis, taking into account their individual facts, credible and up-to-date country of origin information and relevant case law.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-01-09T17:48:04.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663114/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663114/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663114/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-21","Deportation: Democratic Republic of Congo","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 15 December (HL3748), what steps they are taking to assess the safety of those removed from the UK to the Democratic Republic of Congo, once they are in the Democratic Republic of Congo.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of Durham",,"The Lord Bishop of Durham","HL4329"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663115","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-06","<p>The Renewable Heat Incentive Scheme in Great Britain covers England, Scotland and Wales. Section 113 of the Energy Act 2011 contains provisions to enable the Northern Ireland Executive to make regulations to introduce and operate a Renewable Heat Incentive scheme in Northern Ireland. Records suggest officials from the Department of Energy and Climate Change (now the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy - BEIS) discussed the introduction of these provisions with officials in the Northern Ireland Executive.</p><p> </p><p>BEIS does not hold records of any subsequent discussion with the Northern Ireland Executive in relation to the design or operation of the Northern Ireland Renewable Heat Incentive scheme until March 2016 when the Department of Enterprise, Trade and Investment confirmed the closure of the RHI scheme in Northern Ireland. There is no record of advice being provided on the Northern Ireland Renewable Heat Incentive scheme’s compliance with EU law.</p><p> </p><p>BEIS has engaged closely with the Welsh and Scottish Governments on all amendments to the Renewable Heat Incentive scheme in Great Britain, and informed the Northern Ireland Executive in parallel.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2017-01-06T14:03:16.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663115/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663115/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663115/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-21","Renewable Energy","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answers by Baroness Neville-Rolfe on 20 December (HL3914, HL3915, HL3916), whether the fact that renewable energy is a devolved matter means that they did not have any discussions or consultations with the Northern Ireland Executive during or after the introduction of the Northern Ireland Renewable Heat Incentive scheme; whether advice was given to the Northern Ireland Executive regarding the Northern Ireland Renewable Heat Incentive scheme’s compliance with EU law; and what discussions they have had with the Scottish and Welsh governments regarding their implementation of renewable energy schemes.","false","Biography information for Lord Empey",,"Lord Empey","HL4330"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663116","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Northern Ireland Executive’s budget allocation from the Treasury for renewable heat schemes has been set through to 2019-20 and is set out in the table below. Spending in relation to this allocation can only be used to support renewable heat schemes.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>2017-18</p></td><td><p>2018-19</p></td><td><p>2019-20</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>£18.3m</p></td><td><p>£22.3m</p></td><td><p>£25.7m</p></td><td><p>£28.9m</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Allocations for future years will be set out at future Spending Reviews in the normal way.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2017-01-09T14:07:56.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663116/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663116/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663116/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-21","Northern Ireland Renewable Heat Incentive Scheme","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how much money remains available to the Northern Ireland Executive to promote renewable heating schemes; and what conditions, if any, apply for accessing such funds.","false","Biography information for Lord Empey",,"Lord Empey","HL4331"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663117","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-13","<p>There is no formal definition of “reviews”. We regularly review our policies, programmes, and projects to ensure that they meet their intended objectives. Important announcements are made to Parliament by way of ministerial statements, replies to parliamentary questions, or in debate contributions by Ministers.</p><p>The information requested is not collated centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-01-13T14:19:46.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663117/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663117/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663117/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-21","Department for Communities and Local Government: Reviews","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many reviews have been announced in Parliament by the Department for Communities and Local Government in the last six years; how many have been completed; how many are still ongoing; and what is the timescale for completion of those reviews still ongoing.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL4332"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663118","Home Office","false","2017-01-11","<p>All announcements by Ministers in my Department are placed in the Parliamentary records.</p><p>Accounts of progress are given within the normal course of Parliamentary business.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-01-11T12:11:48.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663118/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663118/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663118/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-21","Home Office: Reviews","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many reviews have been announced in Parliament by the Home Office in the last six years; how many have been completed; how many are still ongoing; and what is the timescale for completion of those reviews still ongoing.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL4333"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663119","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-09","<p>There is no formal definition of “reviews”. The Department regularly reviews policies, programmes, projects and pilots to ensure that they meet their objectives. All important announcements are made to Parliament first by way of ministerial statements, replies to parliamentary questions, or in debate contributions by Ministers.</p><p> </p><p>The information requested is not collated centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>",,"Lord Henley",,"2017-01-09T15:46:49.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663119/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663119/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663119/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-21","Department for Work and Pensions: Reviews","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many reviews have been announced in Parliament by the Department for Work and Pensions in the last six years; how many have been completed; how many are still ongoing; and what is the timescale for completion of those reviews still ongoing.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL4334"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663120","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-30","<p>There is no formal definition of “reviews”. All announcements by Ministers in my Department are placed in Parliamentary records.</p><p> </p><p>Accounts of progress are given within the normal course of Parliamentary business.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2017-01-30T16:52:02.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663120/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663120/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663120/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-21","Ministry of Justice: Reviews","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many reviews have been announced in Parliament by the Ministry of Justice in the last six years; how many have been completed; how many are still ongoing; and what is the timescale for completion of those reviews still ongoing.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL4335"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663121","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-01-09","<p>This information is not held centrally and too obtain it would incur a disproportionate cost.</p>",,"Lord Ashton of Hyde",,"2017-01-09T16:34:57.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663121/answer","Biography information for Lord Ashton of Hyde","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663121/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663121/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-12-21","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Reviews","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many reviews have been announced in Parliament by the Department of Culture, Media and Sports in the last six years; how many have been completed; how many are still ongoing; and what is the timescale for completion of those reviews still ongoing.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL4336"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663122","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-09","<p>Since 1 January 2011 the Ministry of Defence has announced 11 reviews in Parliament, of which 10 have been completed and one, the Review of the Service Museums announced on 15 October 2015 (HLWS241), is due to be completed shortly.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2017-01-09T16:24:01.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663122/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663122/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663122/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-21","Ministry of Defence: Reviews","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many reviews have been announced in Parliament by the Ministry of Defence in the last six years; how many have been completed; how many are still ongoing; and what is the timescale for completion of those reviews still ongoing.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL4337"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663123","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-09","<p>We are unable to provide the data on the number of men and women currently in custody on fixed term recall. Whilst this information is held on individual case files, a manual exercise would be required to locate and collate this information. Such an exercise would incur disproportionate cost.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2017-01-09T17:59:02.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663123/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663123/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663123/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-21","Reoffenders","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many (1) men, and (2) women, are currently in prison having broken the terms of their licences on a fixed-term recall.","false","Biography information for Lord Marks of Henley-on-Thames",,"Lord Marks of Henley-on-Thames","HL4338"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663124","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-09","<p>The recall of offenders who are serving their sentence on licence and in the community is a preventative measure. It is instigated by the probation services only when the offender’s behaviour or non-compliance with their licence conditions suggest that they present as an increased risk of harm to the public or an increased risk of committing further offences.</p><p> </p><p>There has been no estimate of the cost to the various agencies of recalling offenders on licence during the last 12 months, but any such cost would have to be offset by the potential costs arising from the offender remaining in the community and committing further offences.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2017-01-09T17:59:41.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663124/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663124/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663124/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-21","Reoffenders","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what estimate they have made of the cost of returning people to prison following breaches of their licences during the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Lord Marks of Henley-on-Thames",,"Lord Marks of Henley-on-Thames","HL4339"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663125","Department of Health","false","2017-01-09","<p>Information on average waiting times over the last 12 months for transfer of prisoners who have been assessed as requiring transfer to a secure hospital is not held in the format requested.</p><p> </p><p>Information on the number of secure beds is not held in the format requested. Secure hospital beds are not specifically allocated to either prisoners or people in the community, but are allocated according to clinical need for all people who need them.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy","HL4341","2017-01-09T13:15:33.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663125/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663125/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663125/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-21","High Security Hospitals","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the average waiting time over the last 12 months for transfer for (1) male, and (2) female, prisoners who have been assessed as requiring transfer to a secure hospital.","false","Biography information for Lord Marks of Henley-on-Thames",,"Lord Marks of Henley-on-Thames","HL4340"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663126","Department of Health","false","2017-01-09","<p>Information on average waiting times over the last 12 months for transfer of prisoners who have been assessed as requiring transfer to a secure hospital is not held in the format requested.</p><p> </p><p>Information on the number of secure beds is not held in the format requested. Secure hospital beds are not specifically allocated to either prisoners or people in the community, but are allocated according to clinical need for all people who need them.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy","HL4340","2017-01-09T13:15:34.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663126/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663126/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663126/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-21","High Security Hospitals","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many secure hospital beds are available for (1) male, and (2) female, prisoners in each region of England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Lord Marks of Henley-on-Thames",,"Lord Marks of Henley-on-Thames","HL4341"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663127","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-09","<p>We are investing £1.3 billion to reform and modernise the prison estate to make it more efficient, safer and focused on supporting prisoner rehabilitation. We will build new prisons and close prisons that are in poor condition and those which do not have a long-term future in the estate. We will also simplify the organisation of the estate so prisoners are placed at the right level of security in prisons with appropriately tailored regimes. This will ensure that the supply of places providing rehabilitation and resettlement services, and those that serve the courts, are balanced with demand.</p><p>Data on the number of prisoner transfers due to shortages of space is not held centrally.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2017-01-09T18:01:21.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663127/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663127/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663127/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-21","Prisoners' Transfers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many prison transfers owing to shortage of space have taken place in each month over the last 12 months in each prison in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Lord Marks of Henley-on-Thames",,"Lord Marks of Henley-on-Thames","HL4342"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663128","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-13","<p>Information about the use of constant supervision in prisons is not centrally collected.</p><p>All prisons are required to have procedures in place to identify, manage and support people who are at risk of harm to themselves. These include the Assessment, Care in Custody and Teamwork (ACCT) process, which is a prisoner-centred, flexible care planning system for those identified as at risk of suicide or self-harm.</p><p>A prisoner will be placed under constant supervision where that is determined to be necessary to address an immediate suicidal crisis. Such supervision will be one of a number of supportive measures put in place to manage the risk and will remain in place only for so long as is strictly necessary.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2017-01-13T11:50:49.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663128/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663128/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663128/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-21","Prisoners: Suicide","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many female prisoners have been placed on 24-hour watch on at least one occasion in each women’s prison in each of the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Lord Marks of Henley-on-Thames",,"Lord Marks of Henley-on-Thames","HL4343"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663129","Home Office","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Government has transferred more than 900 unaccompanied children to the UK this year under both the family reunification provisions of the Dublin Regulation and the terms of section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016. This includes more than 750 children from France as part of the UK’s support for the Calais camp clearance almost half of the unaccompanied children who were in the camp at the time of the clearance.</p><p>We have consulted local authorities on their capacity to care for unaccompanied asylum seeking and refugee children and will publish the total number of children to be transferred under section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016 in due course.</p><p>In July, the Home Office increased the funding provided to local authorities by up to 33 percent for the care and support of unaccompanied asylum seeking and refugee children. The recent operation to transfer children from Calais involved over 300 officials at home and abroad and the Government continues to work closely with partners across Europe to ensure the timely and effective operation of the Dublin Regulation. We have seconded experts to France and Greece, and we have a long standing secondee in Italy to support the work on unaccompanied asylum seeking children in Europe, including the Dublin Regulation.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL4345 ; HL4346 ; HL4347 ; HL4348","2017-01-09T17:53:42.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663129/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663129/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663129/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-21","Refugees: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many children have been brought to the UK in 2016 under section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016 from (1) France, (2) Greece, and (3) Italy.","false","Biography information for Baroness Massey of Darwen",,"Baroness Massey of Darwen","HL4344"
