"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663132","Home Office","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Government has transferred more than 900 unaccompanied children to the UK this year under both the family reunification provisions of the Dublin Regulation and the terms of section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016. This includes more than 750 children from France as part of the UK’s support for the Calais camp clearance almost half of the unaccompanied children who were in the camp at the time of the clearance.</p><p>We have consulted local authorities on their capacity to care for unaccompanied asylum seeking and refugee children and will publish the total number of children to be transferred under section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016 in due course.</p><p>In July, the Home Office increased the funding provided to local authorities by up to 33 percent for the care and support of unaccompanied asylum seeking and refugee children. The recent operation to transfer children from Calais involved over 300 officials at home and abroad and the Government continues to work closely with partners across Europe to ensure the timely and effective operation of the Dublin Regulation. We have seconded experts to France and Greece, and we have a long standing secondee in Italy to support the work on unaccompanied asylum seeking children in Europe, including the Dublin Regulation.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL4344 ; HL4345 ; HL4346 ; HL4348","2017-01-09T17:53:42.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663132/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663132/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663132/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-21","Refugees: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many Home Office staff are working on resettlement under section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016 in (1) France, (2) Greece, and (3) Italy.","false","Biography information for Baroness Massey of Darwen",,"Baroness Massey of Darwen","HL4347"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663133","Home Office","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Government has transferred more than 900 unaccompanied children to the UK this year under both the family reunification provisions of the Dublin Regulation and the terms of section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016. This includes more than 750 children from France as part of the UK’s support for the Calais camp clearance almost half of the unaccompanied children who were in the camp at the time of the clearance.</p><p>We have consulted local authorities on their capacity to care for unaccompanied asylum seeking and refugee children and will publish the total number of children to be transferred under section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016 in due course.</p><p>In July, the Home Office increased the funding provided to local authorities by up to 33 percent for the care and support of unaccompanied asylum seeking and refugee children. The recent operation to transfer children from Calais involved over 300 officials at home and abroad and the Government continues to work closely with partners across Europe to ensure the timely and effective operation of the Dublin Regulation. We have seconded experts to France and Greece, and we have a long standing secondee in Italy to support the work on unaccompanied asylum seeking children in Europe, including the Dublin Regulation.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL4344 ; HL4345 ; HL4346 ; HL4347","2017-01-09T17:53:42.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663133/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663133/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663133/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-21","Asylum: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many Home Office staff are working on resettlement under the family reunion provisions of the Dublin Regulation in (1) France, (2) Greece, and (3) Italy.","false","Biography information for Baroness Massey of Darwen",,"Baroness Massey of Darwen","HL4348"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663134","Department for Education","false","2017-01-09","<p>We want all schools to provide young people with a broad and balanced curriculum that equips them for success in modern Britain. High quality personal, social, health and economic (PSHE) education has an important role to play in this by helping young people understand the world around them, building resilience and helping them to make positive choices and stay safe.</p><p> </p><p>Sex education is compulsory in secondary maintained schools. The Government is clear that all schools should make provision for high quality, age-appropriate sex and relationship education (SRE) which is a vital part of preparing young people for life.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s current approach is for schools to develop their own local PSHE programme to reflect the needs of their pupils. For some schools, their PSHE programme may include elements of SRE.</p><p>The Secretary of State agrees that we need to look again at the case for further action on PSHE and SRE provision, as a matter of priority with particular consideration to improving quality and accessibility. We are actively considering all our options and will give a view soon.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2017-01-09T14:06:11.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663134/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663134/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663134/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-21","Personal, Social, Health and Economic Education","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will ensure that sex and relationship education will form part of a wider programme of personal, social and health education, including skills for life and character building.","false","Biography information for Baroness Massey of Darwen",,"Baroness Massey of Darwen","HL4349"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663135","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-05","<p>There are no plans to upgrade or change the function of Tornado, which is due to be withdrawn from service in 2019. Under Project Centurion, Typhoon is currently undergoing a series of upgrades. These include the integration of Meteor, Brimstone and Storm Shadow missiles, allowing the transition of our air attack capability to Typhoon when Tornado is finally withdrawn from service.</p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2017-01-05T14:52:09.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663135/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663135/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663135/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-21","Military Aircraft","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have for (1) upgrading, or (2) changing the purpose or function of, (a) Typhoon, and (b) Tornado, aircraft.","false","Biography information for Lord Moonie",,"Lord Moonie","HL4350"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663136","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-05","<p>The planned out of service date for Tornado is 2019 and for Typhoon it is 2040.</p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2017-01-05T14:52:41.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663136/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663136/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663136/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-21","Military Aircraft","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government under current plans, when will the last (1) Tornado, and (2) Typhoon, aircraft leave service.","false","Biography information for Lord Moonie",,"Lord Moonie","HL4351"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663137","Home Office","false","2017-01-10","<p>This is an operational matter for the police and it would not be appropriate for the Department to undertake a review of police actions in this case.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-01-10T13:01:57.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663137/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663137/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663137/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-21","Sexual Offences: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 6 December (HL3671) concerning the actions taken by police after the victim of Keith and Caroline Baker was reported missing from her home in England in 2004, why no assessment has been made; and whether they now intend to review the actions taken by police.","false","Biography information for Lord Morrow",,"Lord Morrow","HL4352"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663138","Home Office","false","2017-01-12","<p>Independent Chief Inspector of Borders and Immigration (ICI) reports are laid before Parliament in compliance with the UK Borders Act 2007.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-01-12T15:42:49.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663138/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663138/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663138/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-21","Independent Chief Inspector of Borders and Immigration","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the impact on the independence of the Chief Inspector of Borders and Immigration of the Home Secretary deciding when to publish his reports.","false","Biography information for Lord Paddick",,"Lord Paddick","HL4353"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663139","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-11","<p>The UK Government is aware of reports of the raid on an Ahmadiyya Muslim office in Rabwah on 5 December and condemns the attack on the Ahmadiyya mosque in Chakwal on 12 December. The Government strongly condemns the persecution of all minorities, including the targeting of people based on their beliefs. Our concerns are reflected in the latest update to the Foreign and Commonwealth Office annual human rights report.</p><p>We regularly raise our concerns about the protection of minority communities, including religious minorities, with the Government of Pakistan. During his visit to Pakistan in November 2016, the Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Mr Johnson), raised religious tolerance and the importance of safeguarding the rights of all Pakistan's citizens. During his visit to Pakistan in January 2017, the Minister for Asia and the Pacific, my Hon. Friend the Member for Reading West (Mr Sharma), raised the protection of minorities, including the Ahmadiyya, with Kamran Michael, Pakistani Minister for Human Rights, and Barrister Zafarullah Khan, the Prime Minister's Special Assistant for Human Rights. The Government continues to urge Pakistan to honour in practice its human rights obligations, including those related to religious minorities, and to uphold the rule of law.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-01-11T12:10:19.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663139/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663139/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663139/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-21","Pakistan: Ahmadiyya","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made to the government of Pakistan about the recent attacks on the Ahmadi mosque in Chakwal, and on the headquarters of the Ahmadiyya Muslim community in Raburah; and about the arrest of Ahmadis in these incidents.","false","Biography information for Lord Pearson of Rannoch",,"Lord Pearson of Rannoch","HL4354"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663140","Home Office","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Code of Practice for Official Statistics, which can be found at https://www.statisticsauthority.gov.uk/publication/code-of-practice/, sets out eight principles to be followed in publishing official statistics, including ‘sound methods and quality assured’.</p><p>Home Office officials continue to review the quality of the information on the number of people claiming asylum on the basis of sexual orientation, which is manually captured by caseworkers through a “special conditions flag” on the Home Office Case Information Database.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-01-09T17:57:47.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663140/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663140/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663140/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-21","Asylum: LGBT People","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 21 December (HL4183) concerning the publication of information on the number of people claiming asylum on the basis of sexual orientation, what reporting standards they have adopted; whether they have assessed that any aspects of those standards are not currently being met; and if any are not, which aspects, and why not.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL4355"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663141","Home Office","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Home Office is committed to publishing data in an orderly way as part of the regular quarterly Immigration Statistics, in line with the Code of Practice for Official Statistics.</p><p>Latest statistics published on 1 December confirmed that a total of 4,414 Syrians have been resettled under the scheme since it began, 4,162 of these arriving in the 12 months to the end of September 2016.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-01-09T17:58:41.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663141/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663141/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663141/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-21","Refugees: Syria","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of their target to resettle 20,000 people via the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Resettlement Programme, how many have been resettled in the UK to date.","false","Biography information for Baroness Sheehan",,"Baroness Sheehan","HL4356"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663142","Home Office","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Vulnerable Childrens Resettlement (VCR) scheme has been designed with the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) to resettle ‘vulnerable children’ and their families from the Middle East and North Africa (MENA) region.</p><p>The Government has committed to resettling several hundred individuals in the first year with a view to resettling up to 3,000 individuals over the lifetime of this Parliament. Children who are identified as at risk will be resettled with their family members or carers where appropriate. The Home Office is committed to publishing data in an orderly way as part of the regular quarterly Immigration Statistics, in line with the Code of Practice for Official Statistics. The figures for the VCR scheme will be published in the usual way, and will feature in future releases of the Home Office’s immigration quarterly statistics. We will not be providing a running commentary.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-01-09T18:00:29.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663142/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663142/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663142/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-21","Refugees: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of their commitment to resettle 3,000 unaccompanied minors from the Middle East and North Africa, how many have been resettled in the UK to date.","false","Biography information for Baroness Sheehan",,"Baroness Sheehan","HL4357"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663143","Home Office","false","2017-01-09","<p>We have been working closely with the French authorities to bring eligible children eligible to the UK under the Dublin Regulation and the wider criteria of the Immigration Act. Since 10 October, more than 750 children have arrived.</p><p>This is in line with the commitments made by the Home Secretary to Parliament on 24 October. We will publish a total number of transfers as a result of the operation in France in due course.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-01-09T18:01:42.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663143/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663143/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663143/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-21","Asylum: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many unaccompanied minors from the Calais camp known as the Jungle have been transferred to the UK since 2 November (1) through the Dublin III family reunification route; and (2) through provision made under section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016.","false","Biography information for Baroness Sheehan",,"Baroness Sheehan","HL4358"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663144","Department for Education","true","2017-01-09","<p>The Government does not collect data on the number of schools that invite outside organisations to provide careers advice and guidance to pupils.</p><p> </p><p>Schools have a duty to secure independent careers guidance on the full range of education and training options, including apprenticeships and other technical education options. Sources of independent careers guidance can include, but not be limited to, external organisations such as education and training providers, employers and careers<ins class="ministerial">professionals.</ins> <del class="ministerial">providers.</del></p><p> </p><p>The Government’s statutory guidance on careers is clear that schools should give other providers who wish to do so the opportunity to engage with pupils, on school premises, to inform them directly about what they offer. These could include further education and sixth form colleges, studio schools, university technical colleges and employers and other providers delivering apprenticeships.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has established The Careers &amp; Enterprise Company to increase the level of employer input into schools. The Company’s Enterprise Adviser Network is now live in over 1,300 <del class="ministerial">of the</del> secondary schools and colleges across the country, connecting young people with local employers to provide experiences of the workplace.</p><p> </p><p>Careers organisations provide another external source of advice and guidance. The statutory guidance encourages schools to consult a register of accredited careers organisations when securing access to face-to-face careers guidance.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2017-01-09T17:56:09.203Z","2017-01-10T15:05:49.997Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663144/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663144/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663144/answer",,"Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663144/answer/previousversion/28926","Biography information for Lord Nash","60","Education","Education","2016-12-21","Schools: Vocational Guidance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many (1) maintained schools, (2) academies, and (3) free schools, invited outside organisations to provide careers guidance and advice to their pupils in the academic years (a) 2013–14, (b) 2014–15, and (c) 2015–16.","false","Biography information for Lord Watson of Invergowrie",,"Lord Watson of Invergowrie","HL4359"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663145","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Department for Culture, Media and Sport has had no such discussions with the British Olympic Association. The participation of British athletes in the 2019 European Games is ultimately a decision for the British Olympic Association and the appropriate National Governing Bodies of Sport.</p>",,"Lord Ashton of Hyde",,"2017-01-09T16:06:07.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663145/answer","Biography information for Lord Ashton of Hyde","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663145/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663145/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-12-21","European Games: Belarus","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what discussions they have had, or plan to have, with the British Olympic Committee concerning the presence of UK athletes at the 2019 European Games, in the light of the human rights record of the host country, Belarus.","false","Biography information for Lord Watson of Invergowrie",,"Lord Watson of Invergowrie","HL4360"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663146","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-10","<p>The UK makes regular representations to the Greek Government and United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) on the need for all individuals in refugee camps to be treated in line with internationally recognised humanitarian standards. The UK has committed up to £34 million to help address the migration crisis through the UNHCR, Non-Governmental Organisations, the Red Cross and the International Organisation for Migration. The Secretary of State for International Development, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Witham (Priti Patel) recently announced a new £8 million Women and Girls Protection Fund to protect women, girls and other vulnerable groups in the Mediterranean region, including Greece.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-01-10T14:30:19.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663146/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663146/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663146/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-21","Greece: Migrant Camps","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made to the government of Greece regarding the harassment and persecution of non-Muslims in refugee camps and the provision of appropriate protection.","false","Biography information for Baroness Cox",,"Baroness Cox","HL4361"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663147","Home Office","false","2017-01-10","<p>There is no provision in the Immigration Rules for people to travel to the UK to claim asylum and we have no plans to change that. An individual should apply for protection from the authorities in the first available safe country or through the United Nations Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR).</p><p>We work closely with European Union Member States to share best practice on preventing individuals from becoming radicalised and to share information relating to people of interest for law enforcement, immigration and border control purposes.</p><p>Individuals granted refugee status in another Member State are subject to the same visa requirements to enter the UK as other third country nationals. Any person arriving at the UK border is subject to stringent security checks and we will deny entry to individuals who present a risk to national security.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL4364","2017-01-10T12:25:57.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663147/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663147/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663147/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-21","Refugees: Greece","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to ensure that non-Muslim civilians who have been forced to flee from Greek refugee camps are eligible to apply for refugee status in the UK.","false","Biography information for Baroness Cox",,"Baroness Cox","HL4362"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663148","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-10","<p>​We have a regular dialogue with the Greek Government on counter-terrorism matters, including the risks of radicalisation in Greece.</p><p>In addition, we are working with the Greek authorities to identify unaccompanied asylum-seeking children who may be eligible for the transfer of their claim to the UK where they have close family here, and are working with Greece to identify unaccompanied refugee children in line with the Dubs amendment. As part of its humanitarian programming, the Department for International Development has set up the Refugee Children's Fund for Europe (RCFE). The RCFE is a £10 million one-year programme to provide shelter and protection services to children, especially unaccompanied ones, in Greece and the Balkans.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-01-10T14:30:59.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663148/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663148/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663148/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-21","Greece: Migrant Camps","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made to the government of Greece regarding the prevention of radicalisation of unaccompanied minors in refugee camps.","false","Biography information for Baroness Cox",,"Baroness Cox","HL4363"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663149","Home Office","false","2017-01-10","<p>There is no provision in the Immigration Rules for people to travel to the UK to claim asylum and we have no plans to change that. An individual should apply for protection from the authorities in the first available safe country or through the United Nations Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR).</p><p>We work closely with European Union Member States to share best practice on preventing individuals from becoming radicalised and to share information relating to people of interest for law enforcement, immigration and border control purposes.</p><p>Individuals granted refugee status in another Member State are subject to the same visa requirements to enter the UK as other third country nationals. Any person arriving at the UK border is subject to stringent security checks and we will deny entry to individuals who present a risk to national security.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL4362","2017-01-10T12:25:57.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663149/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663149/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663149/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-21","Refugees: Greece","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made to the government of Greece on preventing radicalised refugees from entering the UK.","false","Biography information for Baroness Cox",,"Baroness Cox","HL4364"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663150","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-09","<p>The consultations on the draft airports National Policy Statement on Heathrow Airport and on airspace policy are both matters of national importance in their own right, but are clearly related. The Government intends to bring forward the two consultations at the same time to enable the public and the aviation industry to consider all proposals together. Consulting in parallel can also enable the policy proposals set out in the airspace consultation which are adopted to be in place to influence decisions taken later on in the planning process for a proposed Northwest Runway at Heathrow. Equally, airspace is an important issue and the policy proposals cover the whole country, so it is right that we progress with policy proposals to bring improvements to the way it is handled nationwide.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","HL4366 ; HL4367","2017-01-09T13:26:44.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663150/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663150/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663150/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-21","Heathrow Airport","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government why they propose to designate a national policy statement on the expansion of Heathrow Airport separately from dealing with airspace policy.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hamwee",,"Baroness Hamwee","HL4365"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663151","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-09","<p>The consultations on the draft airports National Policy Statement on Heathrow Airport and on airspace policy are both matters of national importance in their own right, but are clearly related. The Government intends to bring forward the two consultations at the same time to enable the public and the aviation industry to consider all proposals together. Consulting in parallel can also enable the policy proposals set out in the airspace consultation which are adopted to be in place to influence decisions taken later on in the planning process for a proposed Northwest Runway at Heathrow. Equally, airspace is an important issue and the policy proposals cover the whole country, so it is right that we progress with policy proposals to bring improvements to the way it is handled nationwide.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","HL4365 ; HL4367","2017-01-09T13:26:44.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663151/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663151/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663151/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-21","Heathrow Airport","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government  what assessment they have made of whether it is necessary to consult on airspace policy for the UK as a whole before designating a national policy statement on Heathrow Airport.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hamwee",,"Baroness Hamwee","HL4366"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663152","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-09","<p>The consultations on the draft airports National Policy Statement on Heathrow Airport and on airspace policy are both matters of national importance in their own right, but are clearly related. The Government intends to bring forward the two consultations at the same time to enable the public and the aviation industry to consider all proposals together. Consulting in parallel can also enable the policy proposals set out in the airspace consultation which are adopted to be in place to influence decisions taken later on in the planning process for a proposed Northwest Runway at Heathrow. Equally, airspace is an important issue and the policy proposals cover the whole country, so it is right that we progress with policy proposals to bring improvements to the way it is handled nationwide.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","HL4365 ; HL4366","2017-01-09T13:26:44.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663152/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663152/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663152/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-21","Heathrow Airport","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of whether it is possible to undertake proper consultation on a national policy statement on Heathrow Airport and on airspace policy as separate matters.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hamwee",,"Baroness Hamwee","HL4367"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663155","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-09","<p>The latest available estimates produced by the OECD show that the value added from the UK’s gross exports to the European Union accounted for 11.6 per cent of total UK value added in 2011.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2017-01-09T14:08:40.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663155/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663155/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663155/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-21","UK Trade with EU","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what percentage of UK gross domestic product results from exports to the EU single market.","false","Biography information for Lord Pearson of Rannoch",,"Lord Pearson of Rannoch","HL4370"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663156","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Government continues to undertake a range of analyses to inform the UK’s position for the upcoming EU exit negotiations. We are seeking the best possible arrangement for the United Kingdom and the work being conducted reflects this.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2017-01-09T14:09:18.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663156/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663156/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663156/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-21","UK Trade with EU","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of how many jobs in the EU are dependent on EU trade with the UK, and how many UK jobs are dependent on trade with the EU single market.","false","Biography information for Lord Pearson of Rannoch",,"Lord Pearson of Rannoch","HL4371"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663157","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-01-11","<p>If the UK were to leave the EU without alternative trading arrangements in place, WTO rules would require that trade between the UK and the EU would be subject to Most-Favoured Nation (MFN) treatment for goods and services.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2017-01-11T12:11:28.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663157/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663157/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663157/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-12-21","UK Trade with EU","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of what tariffs would be paid by EU exporters on their trade with the UK, and what tariffs would be paid by UK exporters on their trade with the EU single market, if World Trade Organisation tariffs start to apply to UK trade with the EU single market.","false","Biography information for Lord Pearson of Rannoch",,"Lord Pearson of Rannoch","HL4372"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663158","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-01-09","<p>We welcome all contributions to the debate over the domestic and international implications of Brexit. We want to build a national consensus to our approach to the negotiations with the EU. We need to listen and talk to as many organisations, companies and institutions as possible. That is why we are engaging with the devolved administrations and a wide range of stakeholders, including academia, industry, and civil society. As the Prime Minister has said, we need to think through the issues in a sober and considered way. We have been clear that we intend the UK to be an outward-looking and global leader of free trade.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2017-01-09T15:45:14.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663158/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663158/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663158/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-12-21","Brexit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the speech by Lord Bamford on 27 October during the debate on the domestic and international implication of Brexit (HL Deb, cols 347–8), and whether it will have any effect on their Brexit negotiating position.","false","Biography information for Lord Pearson of Rannoch",,"Lord Pearson of Rannoch","HL4373"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663159","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-09","<p>According to the OECD, the Soviet Union’s debt was $56bn in 1989 and $65bn in 1991 when the Soviet Union was dissolved. In April 1993 Russia formally announced that it was assuming responsibility for the entire external debt of the Soviet Union.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2017-01-09T14:07:29.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663159/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663159/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663159/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-21","Debts: USSR","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what was the Soviet Union’s international debt when it collapsed in 1989, and whether they held the new Russian regime responsible for that debt at the time.","false","Biography information for Lord Pearson of Rannoch",,"Lord Pearson of Rannoch","HL4374"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663160","Department of Health","false","2017-01-06","<p>The Department’s Commercial Medicines Unit has continued to procure medicines for hepatitis C as part of a nationally agreed programme, established in 2015, which establishes framework agreements.</p><p> </p><p>The Unit undertakes a six-monthly rolling regional tender programme on behalf of National Health Service trusts in England, which includes all the new hepatitis C medicines on the market at the time of tendering. Regional annual framework agreements are then established for use by NHS trusts.</p><p> </p><p>The costs associated with the regional tender programme are not separately identifiable.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-01-06T13:58:57.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663160/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663160/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663160/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-21","Hepatitis: Drugs","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the NHS Commercial Medicines Unit has procured a new Hepatitis C treatment in the last 12 months; and if so, what was the cost.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL4375"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663161","Department of Health","false","2017-01-06","<p>The guidance issued by the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) in relation to new direct acting antivirals specifically requires Operational Delivery Networks (ODNs) to prioritise hepatitis C patients on the basis of highest unmet clinical need. NHS England’s commitment to treat 10,000 patients in 2016-17, increasing to 12,500 in 2017-18 and rising to 15,000 in 2021 is in line with NICE’s estimate of activity included in the costing tools published to support implementation of the guidance. Each ODN has a number of treatment slots available each month to treat eligible patients. This is known as the monthly treatment run rate, and it ensures the expansion of treatment takes place equitably across the country.</p><p> </p><p>The High Court has considered NHS England’s approach. Its judgement in September 2016 stated “a monthly run rate is not an arbitrary cap but a legitimate way of giving effect to the guidance”.</p><p> </p><p>The planning approach for hepatitis C is set out in the NICE Technological Appraisals 363, 364 and 365.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-01-06T13:58:14.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663161/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663161/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663161/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-21","Hepatitis: Drugs","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether NHS England intends to reassess the cap on new Hepatitis C treatments for patients; and if not, why not.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL4376"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663162","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-09","<p>The National Infrastructure Commission’s (NIC) remit includes all sectors of economic infrastructure, including transport (road, rail, ports and airports). The NIC will examine strategic transport infrastructure when it conducts its first National Infrastructure Assessment.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2017-01-09T14:08:56.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663162/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663162/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663162/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-21","Aviation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to include aviation and airport connectivity in the remit of the National Infrastructure Commission.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL4377"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663163","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-09","<p>National Rail Conditions of Carriage were amended in July 2015, providing passengers with the right to claim compensation in cash rather than only vouchers. Passengers want to be able to claim compensation quickly and simply and that includes getting the payment in the form that suits them best.</p><p> </p><p>From 1 October 2016, under the Consumer Rights Act 2015, where a delay was caused by a fault of the train company, passengers are entitled to payment by the same means as the ticket was paid for unless the passenger agrees to another payment method.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-01-09T13:17:00.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663163/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663163/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663163/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-21","Railways: Compensation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to ensure that train operating companies offer compensation for delays and cancellations in cash rather than in vouchers.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL4378"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663164","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Government expects that the information provided by train operators to passengers wishing to make a claim is easy to find, easy to understand and empowers passengers to claim. The process of claiming must be as quick and straightforward as it can be.</p><p> </p><p>The Government Response to the Which? Super-complaint report outlines the steps that the industry is committed to taking and the role that Government is playing in this, including through franchising.</p><p> </p><p>A copy of this document has been placed in the libraries of both Houses for the convenience of Noble Lords.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-01-09T13:18:06.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663164/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663164/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663164/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-21","Chiltern Railways","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how they intend to ensure that Chiltern Railways improves its performance against the five standards as set out in the <i>Rail Compensation – update report</i> published by the Office of Rail and Road in December.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL4379"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663165","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-09","<p>The framework for implementing airspace modernisation is set out in the Future Airspace Strategy which was published by the Civil Aviation Authority in 2011. Its implementation is a matter for the aviation industry.</p><p> </p><p>To help assist the process of airspace modernisation, the Government intends to consult on airspace policy shortly.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-01-09T13:16:17.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663165/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663165/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/663165/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-21","Air Traffic Control","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to set out a framework for airspace modernisation; and if so, when.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL4380"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662657","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-05","<p>The Government is determined that everyone who is entitled to the National Minimum Wage (NMW) and the National Living Wage (NLW) receives it. Anyone who believes they have been underpaid NMW or NLW should contact the Advisory, Conciliation and Arbitration Service (Acas) helpline on 0300 123 1100. HMRC reviews all complaints referred.</p><p> </p><p>There have been 13 successful prosecutions for NMW offences since 2007, with 4 of these in the 2016 calendar year. However, prosecutions are not necessarily the best approach in most cases. Criminal sanctions against companies mean that workers – the ultimate beneficiaries of enforcing the NMW and NLW – end up waiting longer for their lost earnings to be paid back.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2017-01-05T14:55:47.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662657/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662657/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662657/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-20","Minimum Wage","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Neville-Rolfe on 26 October (HL2092), how many cases relating to failure to pay the minimum wage have been considered for criminal investigation; and how many have led to prosecutions.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL4264"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662658","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-04","<p>Since April 2016, the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy has issued 60 penalty notices as a result of 164 warning notices to employers for failure to comply with orders of employment tribunals to pay compensation to applicants.</p><p> </p><p>As a result of the Employment Tribunal Penalty regime the department has secured over £83,000 in previously unpaid awards for applicants.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2017-01-04T11:10:05.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662658/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662658/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662658/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-20","Employment Tribunals Service","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Neville-Rolfe on 24 October (HL2341), how many penalties have been issued in respect of the failure of employers to pay employment tribunal awards since the new penalty system was introduced in 2016; and with what results.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL4265"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662659","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-05","<p>The Sovereign Grant supports the Monarch’s official business, enabling The Queen to discharge her duties as Head of State. It meets the central staff costs and running expenses of Her Majesty’s official household. It also covers maintenance of the Royal Palaces in England and the cost of travel undertaken by Members of the Royal Family to carry out official engagements.</p><p> </p><p>Together, Members of the Royal Family complete over 3,000 engagements a year across the UK - many more than The Queen could undertake alone.</p><p> </p><p>There are no plans to extend the Grant to other Members of the Royal Family in their own right.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2017-01-05T14:32:35.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662659/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662659/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662659/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-20","Sovereign Grant","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government which members of the Royal Family are in receipt of the Sovereign Grant; and whether they have any plans to extend the provision of the Grant to (1) Princess Beatrice, and (2) Princess Eugenie.","false","Biography information for Lord Berkeley",,"Lord Berkeley","HL4266"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662660","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-04","<p>This will be considered as part of the government’s response to Professor Waterson’s review.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2017-01-04T11:09:34.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662660/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662660/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662660/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-20","Consumer Protection Measures in the Ticket Resale Market Review","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will publish the written submissions received in response to the Waterson review into the consumer protection measures concerning online secondary ticketing facilities which was published on 26 May.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town",,"Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town","HL4267"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662661","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-03","<p>The Competition and Markets Authority is an independent enforcement body and draws on a range of sources when carrying out such investigations. The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy does not hold this evidence.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2017-01-03T14:09:53.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662661/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662661/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662661/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-20","Tickets: Touting","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will publish the evidence collected by the Competition and Markets Authority in relation to the secondary tickets platform compliance review.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town",,"Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town","HL4268"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662662","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-21","<p>Negotiating the details of the UK’s exit will take some time. The status of pensioners will need careful consideration and state pensions will be considered as part of the negotiations.</p>",,"Lord Freud",,"2016-12-21T12:54:32.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662662/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662662/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662662/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-20","State Retirement Pensions: British Nationals Abroad","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will give an assurance to UK citizens living in the EU and in receipt of the UK basic state pension that they will continue to receive the annual pension increase when the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Lord Jones of Cheltenham",,"Lord Jones of Cheltenham","HL4269"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662663","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-05","<p>The Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency is currently revising the MOT Inspection Manual for cars and light goods vehicles to enable compliance with EU Directive 2014/45/EU. This includes amended advice to detect where catalytic converters and diesel particulate filters have been removed from vehicles where they were fitted as standard. It will be issued by summer 2017.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-01-05T14:28:46.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662663/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662663/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662663/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-20","Motor Vehicles: Exhaust Emissions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when the Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency will provide information to MoT testers enabling them to confirm that originally fitted catalytic converters and diesel particulate filters are present and operating effectively.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb",,"Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb","HL4270"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662664","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-05","<p>Since 1 January 2016 a total of 4,925 cars and light vans have failed an MOT test in GB for defects with the catalytic converter and a further 468 have failed the MOT test for problems with the diesel particulate filter. The Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency cannot readily separate figures for the London area, and does not have figures from Northern Ireland, as this is a devolved issue.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-01-05T14:30:17.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662664/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662664/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662664/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-20","Motor Vehicles: Exhaust Emissions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many cars have failed an MoT test since 1 January 2016 as a result of problems with originally fitted catalytic converters or diesel particulate filters, in (1) the UK, and (2) the London area.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb",,"Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb","HL4271"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662665","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-05","<p>The Department for Transport has commissioned research by Ricardo Ltd into how new technology can improve detection of diesel particulate filter removal or the effectiveness of such a filter. It is not possible to give a timescale at this early stage to determine how these findings may be used.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-01-05T14:27:20.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662665/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662665/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662665/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-20","Motor Vehicles: Exhaust Emissions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their timescale for developing methods which can detect the removal or effectiveness of a particulate filter during an MoT check-up; whether they have commissioned research into this; and if so, from whom.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb",,"Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb","HL4272"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662666","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-05","<p>Garages conducting such modifications to particulate filters are generally not MOT garages – and so the Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency (DVSA) would not consider such a database to be of value. Where the garage making modifications is an authorised MOT garage, DVSA will take appropriate action against them.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-01-05T14:21:41.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662666/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662666/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662666/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-20","Motor Vehicles: Exhaust Emissions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have considered requiring all authorised MoT test centres to enter information on a database whenever they remove the internal core of a particulate filter, so that other test centres can be required to check with the vehicle’s owner that the filter is working again when it is presented for MoT.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb",,"Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb","HL4273"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662667","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-05","<p>Existing legislation makes the owner or user of the vehicle responsible for its condition. Removal of a diesel particulate filter will almost invariably result in a contravention of the regulations, making the vehicle illegal to use on the road. The potential penalties are £1,000 for a car and £2,500 for a van. Action can be taken against garages who are promoting services in a way that makes it likely car owners will break the law by making such changes to their vehicle.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-01-05T14:29:34.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662667/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662667/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662667/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-20","Motor Vehicles: Exhaust Emissions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what action they will pursue against garages, drivers or others whose actions have contributed to the illegal driving of vehicles without an originally fitted catalytic converter and diesel particulate filter.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb",,"Baroness Jones of Moulsecoomb","HL4274"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662668","Department for Education","false","2017-01-11","<p>We will publish the Government response to the consultation on the implementation of the English Baccalaureate policy in due course.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2017-01-11T15:00:51.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662668/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662668/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662668/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-20","English Baccalaureate","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they plan to announce the results of their consultation on the English Baccalaureate which closed in January.","false","Biography information for Lord Lexden",,"Lord Lexden","HL4275"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662669","Department of Health","false","2017-01-06","<p>The Government published its response to the Independent Review on Antimicrobial resistance, on the 16 September 2016. A copy of the response, <em>Government response to the Review on Antimicrobial Resistance September 2016</em>, is attached.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s response strongly supported the recommendations to use global financing to reinvigorate both early stage research and the development of new drugs. We continue to work internationally, most recently at the United Nations, to support global action on antimicrobial resistance.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-01-06T14:07:42.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662669/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662669/answer","Gov_response_AMR_Review.pdf","Govt response AMR review","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662669/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-20","Antimicrobial Resistance Review","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they will publish their response to the independent <i>Review on Antimicrobial Resistance</i>, published on 19 May.","false","Biography information for Baroness Masham of Ilton",,"Baroness Masham of Ilton","HL4276"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662670","Cabinet Office","false","2017-01-09","<p>The Government is committed to helping the lowest paid. We are the first government to introduce a compulsory Living Wage. From 1<sup>st</sup> April 2016, the new National Living Wage was introduced for workers aged 25 and above, initially set at £7.20 per hour.</p><p>The Chancellor announced a further increase to the National Living Wage in the Autumn Statement. As of 1<sup>st</sup> April 2017, the National Living Wage will be set at £7.50 per hour.</p><p>The Low Pay Commission advises the Government on the rate of annual increases required to achieve a National Living Wage that will represent 60% of median earnings by 2020. The Low Pay Commission amended its recommendations this year to meet this target, based on the latest market forecasts. In light of these changes, government departments are currently reviewing the cost and number of civil servants that will benefit from future National Living Wage increases.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2017-01-09T13:14:58.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662670/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662670/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662670/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-12-20","Civil Servants: Minimum Wage","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many civil service employees are paid the minimum wage; and what the implementation of the National Living Wage for civil servants will cost.","false","Biography information for Lord Moonie",,"Lord Moonie","HL4277"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662671","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-05","<p>The Forward Fleet comprises serviceable and short term unserviceable aircraft. Typically the short term unserviceable aircraft are undergoing minor works, forward maintenance or any other unforeseen rectification or technical inspection that can arise on a day-to-day basis. The Sustainment Fleet includes aircraft undergoing deep maintenance, upgrade programmes or being held in storage.</p><p> </p><p>The total in service Typhoon fleet is 134 airframes, of which 91 airframes are in the Forward Fleet and 43 airframes are in the Sustainment Fleet.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2017-01-05T14:49:02.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662671/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662671/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662671/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-20","European Fighter Aircraft","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many Typhoon fighter aircraft are in service; how many are serviceable; how many could be serviceable within a week; how many are in longer-term maintenance; and whether any are considered to be in reserve.","false","Biography information for Lord Moonie",,"Lord Moonie","HL4278"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662672","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-05","<p>The UK has taken delivery of 134 out of 160 Typhoon aircraft ordered, with the remaining 26 expected to be delivered by summer 2019.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2017-01-05T14:50:41.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662672/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662672/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662672/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-20","European Fighter Aircraft","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether any Typhoon aircraft are yet to be delivered; and if so, to what timescale.","false","Biography information for Lord Moonie",,"Lord Moonie","HL4279"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662673","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-05","<p>I am withholding the information requested as its disclosure would, or would be likely to, prejudice the capability, effectiveness or the security of the Armed Forces.</p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2017-01-05T14:51:30.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662673/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662673/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662673/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-20","Military Aircraft","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many pilots currently serving in the RAF are qualified to fly (1) the Typhoon, and (2) the Tornado, aircraft.","false","Biography information for Lord Moonie",,"Lord Moonie","HL4280"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662674","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-05","<p>The time required to retrain a Tornado pilot to fly a Typhoon aircraft is dependent on a number of factors. However, generally it is expected to take 24 weeks, which is the time to complete the full Typhoon Operational Conversion Unit course.</p><p> </p><p>Information regarding the cost to retrain a Tornado pilot to fly a Typhoon aircraft is not held centrally and could be provided only at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2017-01-05T14:45:39.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662674/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662674/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662674/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-20","European Fighter Aircraft","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the length of time and cost required to retrain a Tornado pilot to fly a Typhoon aircraft.","false","Biography information for Lord Moonie",,"Lord Moonie","HL4281"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662675","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-05","<p>The Forward Fleet comprises serviceable and short term unserviceable aircraft. Typically the short term unserviceable aircraft are undergoing minor works, forward maintenance or any other unforeseen rectification or technical inspection that can arise on a day-to-day basis. The Sustainment Fleet includes aircraft undergoing deep maintenance, upgrade programmes or being held in storage.</p><p> </p><p>The total in service Tornado GR4 fleet is 68 airframes, of which 46 are in the Forward Fleet and 22 are in the Sustainment Fleet.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2017-01-05T14:50:01.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662675/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662675/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662675/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-20","Tornado Aircraft","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many Tornado fighter aircraft are in service; how many are serviceable; how many could be serviceable within a week; how many are in longer-term maintenance; and whether any are considered to be in reserve.","false","Biography information for Lord Moonie",,"Lord Moonie","HL4282"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662676","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-23","<p>The review is considering how well the Transforming Rehabilitation reforms have worked and what changes, if any, are necessary to deliver the policy objectives of reducing reoffending and protecting the public. The timescales for the review reflect its broad scope and the need for close engagement with probation providers. The internal review will inform our more detailed plans which we will publish shortly after the review.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2017-01-23T12:13:20.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662676/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662676/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662676/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-20","Probation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the remarks by the Secretary of State for Justice on 6 December (HC Deb, col 110) concerning the comprehensive review of the probation system, why the review will not be completed until April 2017; whether they intend to provide an update on the interim findings; and whether the findings of the final review will be published.","false","Biography information for Lord Ramsbotham",,"Lord Ramsbotham","HL4283"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662677","Department of Health","false","2017-01-05","<p>The World Health Organization (WHO) Global Health Sector Strategy on Viral Hepatitis 2016-21 proposes milestones and targets to achieve the aim of eliminating hepatitis C as a major public health threat. The WHO’s strategy highlights the role of prevention activities, including blood safety, safe injections, and harm reduction interventions among people who inject drugs. The strategy also sets a 2030 target that 80% of eligible persons with chronic hepatitis C are treated. A copy of the strategy is attached. An estimated 160,000 persons are currently infected with hepatitis C in England, many of whom are not yet diagnosed.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-01-05T12:32:55.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662677/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662677/answer","Draft Global Health Sector Strategies - Viral Hepatitis 2016-21.pdf","WHO strategy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662677/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-20","Hepatitis","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many people they estimate will need to receive hepatitis C treatment in England over the next 13 years in order to achieve the World Health Organisation's goal of eliminating hepatitis C by 2030.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL4284"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662678","Department of Health","false","2017-01-04","<p>Information on treatments prescribed and purchased privately online is not collected.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-01-04T11:09:04.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662678/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662678/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662678/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-20","Hepatitis","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many people in England have purchased hepatitis C treatments online and are currently being monitored by the NHS.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL4285"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662679","Department of Health","false","2017-01-06","<p>The United Kingdom has a comprehensive surveillance system in place combining laboratory diagnoses data, risk behaviour data, outcome data, statistical modelling and service evaluation. This enables the health and social care system to monitor the cascade of care (the pathway for testing and diagnosis to contact with health services through to treatment and outcomes), detect outbreaks, and generate burden estimates. Prevention efforts in minimising harm to people who inject drugs are focused on increasing access to opiate substitution therapies and needle syringe exchange programmes, and the use of disinfection tablets in prisons. NHS England leads on treatment and continues to support National Health Service-led Operational Delivery Networks to provide National Institute for Health and Care Excellence approved treatments for hepatitis C.</p><p> </p><p>Public Health England supports the Government’s efforts by publishing hepatitis C metrics which are available in the report <em>Hepatitis C in the UK 2016 report: Working towards its elimination as a major public health threat</em>. A copy of the report is attached.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-01-06T14:02:12.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662679/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662679/answer","HL 4286 Hepatitis_C_in_the_UK_2016_report.pdf","Hepatitis C in the UK report","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662679/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-20","Hepatitis","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Prior of Brampton on 21 November (HL3153), what plans they have to produce a national improvement framework for hepatitis C.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL4286"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662680","Home Office","false","2017-01-10","<p>The Government has transferred more than 750 children to the UK in support of the French operation to clear the Calais camp under both the family reunification provisions of the Dublin Regulation and the terms of section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016.</p><p>More eligible children will be transferred from Europe, in line with the terms of the Immigration Act, in the coming months and we will continue to meet our obligations under the Dublin Regulation.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-01-10T12:56:38.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662680/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662680/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662680/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-20","Refugees: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many children had been brought to the UK under section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016 by 20 December.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL4287"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662681","Home Office","false","2017-01-10","<p>The Government has transferred more than 750 children to the UK in support of the French operation to clear the Calais camp under both the family reunification provisions of the Dublin Regulation and the terms of section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016.</p><p>More eligible children will be transferred from Europe, in line with the terms of the Immigration Act, in the coming months and we will continue to meet our obligations under the Dublin Regulation.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-01-10T13:01:03.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662681/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662681/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662681/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-20","Refugees: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016 is still available to unaccompanied children in Europe who meet the defined criteria, on which guidance was published on 8 November.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL4288"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662682","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-05","<p>The A34 is part of the Solent to Midlands Route Strategy. Highways England is in the process of updating the route strategy for the A34 which will inform future bids to government for scheme funding. The updated strategies will be published in spring 2017. The updated strategy will reflect the current capacity issues on the A34 and the development proposals which are due to come forward over the coming years including those that could increase the volume of freight.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-01-05T14:20:21.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662682/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662682/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662682/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-20","Transport: Southampton","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether there is an overall strategy for the long-term development of transport links between Southampton and the Midlands, particularly in regard to the volume of freight carried on the A34.","false","Biography information for Lord Lloyd-Webber",,"Lord Lloyd-Webber","HL4289"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662683","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-05","<p>As the Minister of State for Transport, the Rt Hon John Hayes CBE MP, alluded to previously in the A34 Safety Westminster Hall Debate on the 26<sup>th</sup> October 2016, the stage 3 study report for the Oxford to Cambridge expressway was published on 28 November 2016. This study informs current discussions on the future of the A34.</p><p> </p><p>Highways England is also currently updating their route strategies, including the Solent to Midlands strategy the includes the A34. These strategies will be published in Spring 2017 and will highlight current route issues as well as challenges for the future. This will inform future infrastructure improvement bids. The current Road Investment Strategy announced two schemes on this section of the A34- Technology enhancements between the M4 and M40 and improvements to the Peartree and Botley interchanges. Highways England is working on options for these schemes.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-01-05T14:12:04.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662683/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662683/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662683/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-20","A34","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the proposed Oxford and Cambridge expressway, what is the plan for the A34 north of Chieveley.","false","Biography information for Lord Lloyd-Webber",,"Lord Lloyd-Webber","HL4290"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662684","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-05","<p>The current A34 safety review includes the section south of Chieveley. Improvements are planned to relieve congestion at the interchange between the A34 and the M3 at Junction 9 as set out in the Road Investment Strategy.</p><p> </p><p>Highways England is responsible for the whole of the A34.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-01-05T14:19:23.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662684/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662684/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662684/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-20","A34","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether there are any specific proposals relating to the A34 to the south of the Chieveley interchange; and if so, which agency is responsible for them.","false","Biography information for Lord Lloyd-Webber",,"Lord Lloyd-Webber","HL4291"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662685","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-01-06","<p>Government has given local councils the flexibility they have asked for to bring forward funding for adult social care. The table shows how much each council in Greater Manchester could raise in each year if they chose to use this flexibility in full alongside the existing 2 per cent referendum principle; whether or not they wish to do so would be a matter for each council.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="2"><p>Potential Adult Social Care precept receipts each year with 3 per cent increase</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Greater Manchester Districts</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2017-18</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2018-19</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Manchester</p></td><td><p>£6.7 million</p></td><td><p>£11.5 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Metropolitan Borough of Stockport</p></td><td><p>£6.6 million</p></td><td><p>£11.0 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Tameside</p></td><td><p>£3.7 million</p></td><td><p>£6.3 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Metropolitan Borough of Oldham</p></td><td><p>£4.0 million</p></td><td><p>£6.8 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Metropolitan Borough of Rochdale</p></td><td><p>£3.6 million</p></td><td><p>£6.1 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Metropolitan Borough of Bury</p></td><td><p>£3.5 million</p></td><td><p>£5.8 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Metropolitan Borough of Bolton</p></td><td><p>£4.7 million</p></td><td><p>£7.9 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Metropolitan Borough of Wigan</p></td><td><p>£5.3 million</p></td><td><p>£8.9 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>City of Salford</p></td><td><p>£4.4 million</p></td><td><p>£7.5 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Trafford</p></td><td><p>£4.2 million</p></td><td><p>£7.1 million</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-01-06T14:44:39.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662685/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662685/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662685/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-20","Social Services: Greater Manchester","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how much additional revenue will be raised through the adult social care council tax precept by an increase of (1) three per cent in 2017–18, and (2) three per cent in 2018–19, for each of the 10 districts of Greater Manchester.","false","Biography information for Lord Bradley",,"Lord Bradley","HL4292"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662686","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-01-06","<p>The UK has a long-standing and proud tradition of ensuring our rights and traditional liberties are protected domestically, and of fulfilling our international human rights obligations. The decision to leave the European Union does not change that, and the​ UK will remain committed to its international human rights obligations. We are about to begin negotiations and it would be wrong to set out unilateral positions in advance.<strong><br></strong></p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2017-01-06T14:08:38.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662686/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662686/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662686/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-12-20","Human Rights: EU Law","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will publish a list of the fundamental rights guaranteed under EU law and explain what approach they intend to take towards them before triggering Article 50.","false","Biography information for Lord Lester of Herne Hill",,"Lord Lester of Herne Hill","HL4293"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662687","Home Office","false","2017-01-10","<p>The Government has commenced the formal review of the Scrap Metal Dealers Act 2013 as required by section 18 of that Act. We will publish the findings of the review when completed during 2017.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-01-10T16:11:32.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662687/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662687/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662687/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-20","Scrap Metal Dealers Act 2013","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when the Scrap Metal Dealers Act 2013 review will be published on the Home Office website.","false","Biography information for Baroness Whitaker",,"Baroness Whitaker","HL4294"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662688","Home Office","false","2017-01-10","<p>We have asked for written evidence to inform the review of the Scrap Metal Dealers Act 2013 to be submitted by 30 January 2017.</p><p>We will, however, consider any reasonable request to submit evidence beyond this date, to ensure that we hear from as wide a range of interested parties as possible, including small dealers such as those from Gypsy, Traveller and Roma communities.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-01-10T16:48:18.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662688/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662688/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662688/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-20","Scrap Metal Dealers Act 2013","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will extend the deadline for their consultation on the Scrap Metal Dealers Act 2013 so that small dealers, including those from the Gypsy, Traveller and Roma communities, can contribute.","false","Biography information for Baroness Whitaker",,"Baroness Whitaker","HL4295"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662689","Home Office","false","2017-01-10","<p>The Government is in contact with representatives of the Gypsy, Traveller and Roma communities to enable them to present their evidence relating to the review of the Scrap Metal Dealers Act 2013 orally.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-01-10T16:48:35.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662689/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662689/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662689/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-20","Scrap Metal Dealers Act 2013","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will ensure that oral consultation will be made available to scrap metal dealers from the Gypsy, Traveller and Roma communities during the consultation on the Scrap Metal Dealers Act 2013.","false","Biography information for Baroness Whitaker",,"Baroness Whitaker","HL4296"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662690","Home Office","false","2017-01-10","<p>The formal review of the Scrap Metal Dealers Act 2013 will provide the Government with the opportunity to assess issues relating to scrap metal dealer licences, including the impact of the licensing requirements on scrap metal dealers, including those from the Gypsy, Traveller and Roma communities.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-01-10T16:36:17.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662690/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662690/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662690/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-20","Scrap Metal Dealers Act 2013","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the adverse impact of the Scrap Metal Dealers Act 2013, and in particular its licensing requirements and fees, on dealers from the Gypsy, Traveller and Roma communities.","false","Biography information for Baroness Whitaker",,"Baroness Whitaker","HL4297"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662691","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-05","<p>The UK Government has taken every opportunity to raise Mr Tsege’s case at the very highest levels in Ethiopia. The Ethiopian Government are in no doubt about our concern for Mr Tsege and the priority we place on his wellbeing. We have not directly called for Mr Tsege’s release. The UK does not interfere in the legal system of other countries by challenging convictions, any more than we would accept interference in our judicial system. Our priority is to ensure Mr Tsege’s wellbeing and access to legal advice. We believe that calling for his release would not be successful at this stage and could put at risk the progress that has been made, including our access to Mr Tsege.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-01-05T16:44:06.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662691/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662691/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662691/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-20","Andargachew Tsege","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have made representations to the government of Ethiopia to release the British citizen Mr Andy Tsege; and if not, why not.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL4298"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662692","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-06","<p>The UK Government regularly raises human rights issues with Turkish counterparts. The UK Government is supporting work in Turkey to strengthen the Turkish clothing and textile sector's ability to implement the UN Guiding Principles on Business and Human Rights. The project will bring together business, trade unions and civil society to raise awareness of business's role on human rights, promote workplace social dialogue and address the root causes of human rights issues in the sector, including issues relating to Syrian workers.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-01-06T14:31:37.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662692/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662692/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662692/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-20","Turkey: Migrant Workers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to join with the Turkish Federation of Employers Associations in making representations to the government of Turkey about the exploitation of Syrians working in Turkey and the restrictions on work permits; and whether they plan to discuss those concerns with the International Labour Organisation.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL4299"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662693","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-05","<p>We have regular dialogue with Saudi Arabia and Qatar on Syria. Both states are members of the International Syria Support Group and supporters of the Syrian opposition. The Prime Minister, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Maidenhead (Mrs May), recently discussed Syria with Saudi Arabia and Qatar at the Gulf Cooperation Council summit on 6 December. The Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Boris Johnson) also attended a likeminded Ministerial meeting in Paris on 10 December at which Saudi Arabia and Qatar were represented.</p><p>The Foreign Secretary summoned the Russian and Iranian Ambassadors to the UK on 15 December to express the UK Government's profound concern over the actions of Iran and Russia in Syria. The Foreign Secretary made clear that both states have failed to uphold their obligations under international humanitarian law. It is now imperative that the regime, Russia and Iran implement resolution 2328, providing the UN with unhindered humanitarian access and oversight of evacuation processes to ensure that all civilians and non combatants are properly protected.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-01-05T16:45:09.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662693/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662693/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662693/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-20","Syria: Military Intervention","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether, following their calling-in of Russian and Iranian ambassadors to discuss Syria, they will also call in the ambassadors of Saudi Arabia and Qatar to discuss Syria.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL4300"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662694","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-05","<p>HMRC has a statutory duty of confidentiality and therefore is unable to comment on individual cases.</p><p> </p><p>UK tax law applies to all individuals and organisations that operate within the UK, and HMRC are responsible for ensuring the law is adhered to. Failure by any individual or organisation to comply with their statutory obligations is dealt with consistently.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2017-01-05T14:33:13.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662694/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662694/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662694/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-20","Television: Russia","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether Russian Television, based in Edinburgh, has paid in full all taxes and charges due and complied with any United Kingdom statutory requirements.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL4301"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662696","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-05","<p>The United Kingdom (UK) currently has 21 Service personnel in Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania, as fellow members of NATO. In the Baltic States there is a persistent NATO presence through three NATO Force Integration Units and three NATO-accredited centres of excellence.</p><p> </p><p>Since Russia’s actions in Ukraine, we have continually demonstrated our commitment to regional defence and security by contributing to NATO assurance activity, including: providing ships to NATO’s Standing Naval Forces in the Baltic Sea; deploying RAF Typhoons to deliver Baltic Air Policing; and conducting exercises in the region, with 400 UK personnel participating in exercise SILVER ARROW in October 2016.</p><p> </p><p>At the Warsaw Summit in July 2016, NATO Allies agreed to enhance the Alliance’s presence in the Baltic States and Poland through the deployment of four highly capable battalions. The UK will be lead the Enhanced Forward Presence battalion in Estonia and it is anticipated that up to 800 UK personnel will be deployed in the Spring of 2017. The contributions from NATO Allies will be:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Host Nation</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Framework Nation</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Based</strong> <strong>from</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Contributing Nations</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of Personnel</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Deployed from</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Estonia</p></td><td><p>UK</p></td><td><p>Tapa</p></td><td><p>France, Denmark</p></td><td rowspan="4"><p>Each Enhanced Forward Presence deployment is expected to have around 1,000 personnel, but this will vary over time due to planned rotations of units.</p></td><td rowspan="4"><p>Each Enhanced Forward Presence battalion will be deployed from early 2017.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Latvia</p></td><td><p>Canada</p></td><td><p>Adazi</p></td><td><p>Albania, Italy, Poland, Slovenia</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Lithuania</p></td><td><p>Germany</p></td><td><p>Rukla</p></td><td><p>Belgium, Croatia, France, Luxembourg, Netherlands, Norway</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Poland</p></td><td><p>US</p></td><td><p>Several locations including Żagań, Świętoszów, Skwierzyna, and Bolesławiec</p></td><td><p>Romania, UK</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2017-01-05T14:54:19.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662696/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662696/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662696/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-12-20","Baltic States: Armed Forces","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many British military personnel are now serving in the three Baltic States and what is the current total NATO deployment there.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL4302"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662697","Home Office","false","2017-01-24","<p>Approximately 850 UK linked individuals of national security concern have travelled to engage with the Syrian conflict. We estimate that just under half have returned and approximately 15% are now dead. This number includes all those of national security concern, not just those affiliated with Daesh.</p><p>We estimate that many foreign terrorist fighters from across Europe will choose to remain in the conflict zones, a significant proportion of which are likely to be killed in combat or join other extremist groups in the region. However some may attempt to return to their country of origin.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-01-24T17:55:11.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662697/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662697/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662697/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-20","Syria: Armed Conflict","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their estimate of the number of foreign fighters who have left Syria, and of the proportion of them who may return to Europe.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL4303"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662698","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-05","<p>We are doing everything we can to assist in the gathering and preservation of evidence that could be used in future by judicial bodies to make a judgement on Daesh crimes. We are providing financial support to a specialist organisation to conduct investigations in Syria and build prosecution ready criminal case files against the high level perpetrators, in accordance with international standards. These cases are built for international prosecution should a referral to the International Criminal Court be forthcoming or should individuals be subject to litigation by hybrid, specialised or national courts.</p><p>We are also funding a project through our Human Rights and Democracy Programme, aimed at improving the documentation of sexual violence and other gender based cases in a victim sensitive way, in several areas of Iraq. The project is training a team of human rights defenders to document sexual violence and establish a database of cases across a two year period to inform policy development in the government of Iraq.</p><p>As a first step in the 'Bringing Daesh to Justice' campaign, we are working with the government of Iraq to bring a proposal before the United Nations on evidence gathering and preservation in Iraq. It is vital that this is done now, before evidence is lost or destroyed.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-01-05T16:36:41.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662698/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662698/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662698/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-20","Islamic State: British Nationals Abroad","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether evidence of atrocities committed by individual UK citizens as members of Daesh is being collected; if so, whether this is being done as part of an investigation into sexual violence in the Middle East; and who is collecting this evidence.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL4304"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662699","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-05","<p>The assessment was provided in the review undertaken by Deutsche Gesellschaft für Internationale Zusammenarbeit. This is a German development organisation, commonly known as GIZ and owned by the German government. The September 2013 review, ‘An Overview of Curriculum Reform’, examined the implementation of the 2006 national curriculum across Pakistan.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-01-05T15:32:56.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662699/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662699/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662699/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-12-20","Pakistan: Schools","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Bates on 5 December (HL3360), which organisation or agency independently assessed that the implementation of the 2006 national curriculum by the government of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa was based on the values of democracy, pluralism and peace.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL4305"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662700","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-05","<p>The Department for International Development has taken into consideration a number of reports over recent years which have looked, in part, at implementation of the 2006 national curriculum. These include the November 2011 report from the United States Commission on International Religious Freedom, ‘Connecting the Dots: Education and Religious Discrimination in Pakistan’. The Department is currently supporting the Government of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa to review its textbooks with the aim of improving overall quality and reducing all forms of bias. This work will be completed by March 2018.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-01-05T16:00:19.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662700/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662700/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662700/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-12-20","Pakistan: Schools","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Bates on 5 December (HL3360), what consideration was given by the Department for International Development to other international and local assessments of the implementation of the 2006 national curriculum by the government of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL4306"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662701","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-05","<p>The independent assessment completed in 2013 by Deutsche Gesellschaft für Internationale Zusammenarbeit, ‘An Overview of Curriculum Reform’, looked at the policy implications for government stemming from the new 2006 curriculum. It did not focus specifically on textbooks. The November 2011 report from the United States Commission on International Religious Freedom, ‘Connecting the Dots: Education and Religious Discrimination in Pakistan’, looked in more detail at textbooks, including Urdu textbooks for Grades 1 to 10 across Pakistan. The Sustainable Development Policy Institute, a Pakistani think tank organisation, which carried out this review of textbooks for the Commission, used a team of Pakistani Urdu-speaking nationals.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-01-05T15:59:35.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662701/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662701/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662701/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-12-20","Pakistan: Textbooks","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Bates on 5 December (HL3360), whether, as part of the independent assessment, Urdu books were studied by speakers of Urdu; and if so, which books.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL4307"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662702","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-05","<p>DFID has not undertaken an assessment of the impact of budget cuts by the Government of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa on the education of students from religious minorities. Cuts were reported to have been made by the Department of Auqaf and Minority Affairs for the financial year 2016/17, reducing the funding available for textbooks and fees for pupils attending Christian schools. All UK financial support to education in Khyber Pakhtunkhwa is made through the Elementary and Secondary Education Department in support of the government’s five-year Education Sector Plan which supports government schools attended by pupils of all religious backgrounds. No UK funding goes to the Department of Auqaf and Minority Affairs.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-01-05T15:35:10.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662702/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662702/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662702/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-12-20","Pakistan: Education","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Bates on 5 December (HL3360), what assessment they have made of the impact on the education of students from religious minorities of reductions by the government of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa in the budget reserved for religious minorities.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL4308"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662703","Department for International Development","false","2017-01-05","<p>The Islamic religious seminary Darul Uloom Haqqani receives funding from the Government of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa’s Department of Auqaf and Minority Affairs, however, no UK funding has been provided to that Department. All UK financial support to education in Khyber Pakhtunkhwa is made through the Elementary and Secondary Education Department in support of the government’s five-year Education Sector Plan.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-01-05T15:58:40.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662703/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662703/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662703/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-12-20","Pakistan: Education","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Bates on 5 December (HL3360), what assessment they have made of reports that the government of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa has offered Rs 150 million of British aid funding to the Islamic religious seminary Darul Uloom Haqqani.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL4309"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662704","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-05","<p>We condemn the attack on the Ahmadiyya mosque in Chakwal on 12 December. The Government strongly condemns the persecution of all minorities, including the targeting of people based on their beliefs. Our concerns are reflected in the latest update to the Foreign and Commonwealth Office annual human rights report.</p><p>We regularly raise our concerns about the protection of minority communities, including religious minorities at senior level, with the government of Pakistan. During his visit to Pakistan in November, the Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Mr Johnson) raised religious tolerance and the importance of safeguarding the rights of all Pakistan's citizens. The Government continues to urge Pakistan to honour in practice its human rights obligations, including those related to religious minorities, and to uphold the rule of law.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-01-05T16:46:14.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662704/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662704/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662704/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-12-20","Pakistan: Ahmadiyya","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made to the government of Pakistan about the treatment of Ahmadi Muslims following a recent attack on the Ahmadi Muslim mosque in Chakwal in Pakistan.","false","Biography information for Lord Oates",,"Lord Oates","HL4310"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662705","Department for Education","true","2017-01-06","<p>The Memorandum of Understanding between the Home Office and the Department for Education outlines the purpose and the personal pupil data shared. The Memorandum of Understanding<ins class="ministerial"> has been deposited</ins> <del class="ministerial">is available</del> in the house library.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2017-01-06T14:05:08.593Z","2017-01-10T17:00:14.013Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662705/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662705/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662705/answer",,"Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662705/answer/previousversion/28650","Biography information for Lord Nash","60","Education","Education","2016-12-20","Pupils: Personal Records","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what personal pupil data the Department for Education shares with the Home Office, and for what purpose.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL4311"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662706","Department for Education","false","2017-01-06","<p>The Government recognises how important swift access to defibrillators can be in cases of cardiac arrest. The Government applauds the work of organisations such as the Oliver King Foundation in placing defibrillators locally, and raising awareness of sudden cardiac death.</p><p> </p><p>The Department’s policy is to encourage schools to purchase a defibrillator as part of their first-aid equipment. To help schools to do so, we have negotiated a deal with NHS Supply Chain to offer defibrillators to schools at a reduced cost, and have published advice on installing and maintaining defibrillators on school premises.</p><p> </p><p>Since this scheme was launched in 2014, over 1600 schools have purchased defibrillators through this route. We continue to work with the sector to raise awareness of the scheme and to refine our guidance to schools on installing and maintaining these devices.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2017-01-06T14:04:49.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662706/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662706/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662706/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-20","Schools: Defibrillators","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the Oliver King Foundation's five-year campaign to provide defibrillators in schools and public places, and what plans they have to ensure that every school has a defibrillator.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL4312"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662707","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-19","<p>The average waiting times for immigration and asylum appeals in 2015/16 was 34 weeks.</p><p>As at 30 September 2016 there were 57,290 registered appeals awaiting hearing. This figure is based on internal management information which is not subject to the same rigorous verification processes as published data.</p><p>We do everything we can to avoid unnecessary delay in the Immigration &amp; Asylum Tribunal and we have provided an additional 4,950 tribunal sitting days for this financial year to ensure current caseloads continue to decrease. We are keeping performance under close review.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie","HL4314 ; HL4315","2017-01-19T11:38:34.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662707/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662707/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662707/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-20","Immigration: Appeals","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the average time taken for immigration and asylum tribunals to process and hear cases.","false","Biography information for Lord Ahmed",,"Lord Ahmed","HL4313"
