"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662709","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-19","<p>The average waiting times for immigration and asylum appeals in 2015/16 was 34 weeks.</p><p>As at 30 September 2016 there were 57,290 registered appeals awaiting hearing. This figure is based on internal management information which is not subject to the same rigorous verification processes as published data.</p><p>We do everything we can to avoid unnecessary delay in the Immigration &amp; Asylum Tribunal and we have provided an additional 4,950 tribunal sitting days for this financial year to ensure current caseloads continue to decrease. We are keeping performance under close review.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie","HL4313 ; HL4314","2017-01-19T11:38:34.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662709/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662709/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662709/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-20","Immigration: Appeals","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the speed at which cases are handled in immigration and asylum tribunals in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Lord Ahmed",,"Lord Ahmed","HL4315"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662710","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-01-05","<p>The Northern Ireland Office has had no discussions with the Northern Ireland Executive regarding the protection of Northern Ireland civil servants from inappropriate political interference and influence.</p><p> </p><p>The conduct of the Northern Ireland Civil Service is a devolved matter.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Dunlop",,"2017-01-05T12:19:09.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662710/answer","Biography information for Lord Dunlop","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662710/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662710/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-12-20","Civil Servants: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what discussions they have had with the Northern Ireland Executive concerning the protection of Northern Ireland civil servants from inappropriate political interference and influence.","false","Biography information for Lord Empey",,"Lord Empey","HL4316"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662712","HM Treasury","false","2017-01-05","<p>As set out in the Welsh Government’s fiscal framework, the UK and Welsh governments have agreed to apply a block grant adjustment for each band of income tax separately. Doing so will fully account for the different proportions of basic, higher and additional rate income tax payers in Wales and the rest of the UK.</p><p>This means that the Welsh Government will hold an appropriate set of risks and opportunities regarding their new income tax powers, as part of a wider funding agreement that the UK and Welsh governments agree is fair for Wales and fair for the rest of the UK.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2017-01-05T16:35:26.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662712/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662712/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662712/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-20","Public Expenditure: Wales","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the extent to which the agreement on the government of Wales’ Fiscal Framework published on 19 December compensates for the lower percentage increase in income tax receipts in Wales compared to the UK since 2010–11.","false","Biography information for Lord Hain",,"Lord Hain","HL4318"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662780","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-13","<p>The Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency does not record the number of people sent for prosecution.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","58406","2017-01-13T11:16:25.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662780/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662780/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662780/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-20","Driving Tests: Personation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many people were sent for prosecution for impersonating a candidate and taking the (a) written and (b) practical parts of the driving test for them in each of the last five years and by geographical area.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","58403"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662781","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-13","<p>The majority of these types of investigation are instigated by the Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency (DVSA) and undertaken until such a time as it has evidence to support arrest and possible prosecution.</p><p> </p><p>The attached table shows the:</p><p> </p><ul><li>number of people convicted for using an impersonator to take a theory or practical test in each of the last five years and by geographical area</li><li>number of people convicted for impersonating a candidate to take the theory or practical driving test in each of the last five years and by geographical area.</li></ul>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","58407","2017-01-13T11:09:41.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662781/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662781/answer","058407, 058404 - Driving Tests - Fraud.xlsx","58407, 58404 - Driving Tests - Fraud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/662781/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-20","Driving Tests: Personation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many people were convicted for impersonating a candidate and taking the (a) written and (b) practical parts of the driving test for them in each of the last five years and by geographical area.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","58404"
